<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-Fifth Employees Work Overtime in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Almost one-fifth of all employees
in Canada, an average of 1.9 million people, worked overtime
during the first quarter of 1997, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Of those employees who worked overtime, almost 6 in 10 did not
receive overtime pay," the federal agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Those who did not get paid for their extra time worked an
average of 9.2 overtime hours, compared with 8.5 hours for those
who did get paid.
</P>
<P>
Adult men were twice as likely to get paid overtime as adult
women, since men are more likely to work in manufacturing,
construction and other primary industries where paid overtime is
more common.
</P>
<P>
Youth aged 15 to 24 were less likely to work overtime than
adults, and they put in fewer hours than adults. Unlike adults,
most youths who put in overtime did so for pay.
</P>
<P>
"The proportion of the employed population working long hours
have expanded in recent years," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, the "standard" work week has remained in the range
of 35 to 40 hours a week for many years. "This stability masks
significant shifts in the distribution of work hours, especially
since the 1981-82 recession."
</P>
<P>
By 1995, only 54 percent of workers put in a 35- to 40-hour
work week, down from 65 percent in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, the proportion of workers putting fewer
than 35 hours a week rose from 16 percent to nearly 24 percent,
while the proportion of those usually working 41 hours or more
rose from 19 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Typically, white-collar workers were more likely to have worked
overtime than blue-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1997, one quarter of all those working
overtime were employed as managers. About 37.5 percent of
teachers worked overtime, the highest proportion of any occupation.
</P>
<P>
"Almost all managers and teachers who worked overtime did not
get paid for it," the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
