<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner Urges EU Ban on Tobacco Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Social Affairs
Commissioner Padraig Flynn urged here today all EU member states
to take concrete measures to ban tobacco advertising.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a "smoking summit" in London, Flynn said that all EU
governments had to make concerted efforts to stop the 500,000
deaths every year in Europe from tobacco-related disease.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that it is incumbent on the public health
authorities to make the fight against tobacco a priority for
action," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on EU states to make joint efforts to fight
against tobacco advertising, saying: "The industry has been
organized on an international basis for many years. It is now time
for governments to act in a similarly concerted way."
</P>
<P>
"If not, we will soon find that our citizens will be targeted
by new marketing efforts in a bid to recover lost markets in the
United States and elsewhere," he added.
</P>
<P>
Flynn said that as an urgent matter EU members should look at
the effects of a pending deal under which tobacco companies will
pay 368 billion U.S. dollars to victims of long-time smoking.
</P>
<P>
On the advertising of tobacco, he said the promotion of
tobacco, by direct or indirect advertising, "must be removed and
there can be no continued justification for pushing sales of such
an addictive and deadly product."
</P>
<P>
"While many argue that smoking is a matter of personal choice,
I would add that the addictive properties of tobacco render that
choice a dependency," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The (EU) member states can also adopt a series of measures at
national level to reduce smoking: particularly important here
would be measures to outlaw sales to minors, to restrict vending
machine sales, to improve smoking cessation programs and to
increase taxes on tobacco," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
