<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean FM Reiterates Stance on Japanese Fisheries Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Foreign Minister Yoo
Chong-ha said today that the disputed waters between Japan and
South Korea should be zoned before the 1965 fisheries agreement
between the two countries is revised.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that Japan's seizure of South Korean fishing
boats in waters it recently unilaterally declared part of its
200-nautical-mile exclusive economic zone will not help ease
tensions between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Seoul and Tokyo are currently revising the 1965 agreement on
fishing in disputed waters around a barren outcrop of islands in
the Sea of Japan midway between the two countries and which both
countries lay claim to.
</P>
<P>
But South Korea is insisting the existing deal be respected
until a new pact is drawn up. However, Japan unilaterally
redefined its territorial waters by drawing a straight line
through the disputed waters in January without consulting South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
Since early June, Japan's Maritime Safety Agency has seized
five South Korean fishing boats for trawling in the area.
</P>
<P>
South Korea wants the two sides to zone their waters in line
with the U.N. convention and has said it cannot accept part of the
straight line Japan has drawn to redefine its territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
It has now frozen talks on the new fishing agreement until the
row is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Yoo said today he didn't believe Japan would unilaterally scrap
the fisheries agreement even though negotiations had stopped.
</P>
<P>
"The one-sided scrapping of the fisheries agreement, if any,
will make the overall relations between the two countries very
difficult," Yoo warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
