<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Unveils New Research Into Gulf War Syndrome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The British government announced
here today a new research program into the Gulf War syndrome
suffered by many Gulf War veterans and promised to allocate new
fund to speed up assessments of the mysterious disease.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Armed Forces Minister John Reid said today that the
government is planning a 2.5 million pound (about 4.24 million
U.S. dollar) research program into the possible health effects of
the combination of vaccines and tablets given to Gulf War troops
to protect them against chemical and biological warfare, and
against desert insects.
</P>
<P>
Many Gulf War veterans complained that the syndrome results
from a cocktail of chemicals administered to troops and has
brought problems such as asthma, chronic fatigue, depression and
skin ailments. Some maintain it has resulted in serious birth
defects in their children.
</P>
<P>
Reid noted that the latest government program will be
supervised by an independent panel of experts, including a
representative of the Gulf War veterans.
</P>
<P>
"We have a duty to discharge our responsibilities in respect of
those who have served their country. I aim to see we do just
that," Reid said.
</P>
<P>
About 51,000 British troops served in the Gulf War and up to
4,000 veterans and their families have illnesses. Veterans argued
that evidence gathered in the United States supports the theory
that the "cocktail" of immunizations and pills may be responsible
for the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces minister also stressed that the Labor
government will continue to pay war pensions to those disabled
because of the Gulf War and he also promised that if further
research shows liability, it will pay compensation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
