<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Increase Gold Output, Miners' Wages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Chamber of
Mines and the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) today
announced details of a "historical" accord, under which the
country's gold production will be increased and mine workers
better paid.
</P>
<P>
Both mine workers and their employers hailed the agreement as
being in the best interests of the gold mining industry and as
the best option for its future and stability.
</P>
<P>
Nick Segal, President of the Chamber of Mines, told a press
conference that the accord was "of almost historical
proportions", especially when the two parties agreed to increase
annual gold production by 90 tons countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Chamber of Mines will have mine
workers' wages increased from 10 percent to 25 percent on
condition that productivity and production targets are met.
</P>
<P>
NUM Secretary-General Kgalema Motlanthe described the accord
as a "significant breakthrough", saying it would lay the basis
for sustained growth in the gold mining industry.
</P>
<P>
Segal said the wage offer that comes with the accord is much
higher than ever before, and linked to greater productivity.
</P>
<P>
Motlanthe said the NUM is confident the targets for additional
gold output would be reached as there will be no alternative.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the agreement, about 100,000 mine workers were facing
retrenchment following gold price crash to below 320 U.S. Dollars
an ounce in global market early this month, NUM said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to South Africa, the neighboring Lesotho and
Mozambique are also suffering from the gold slump as tens of
thousands of people from the two countries are working on South
African mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
