<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Gov't Renews Contact With Sinn Fein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Before a new round of Northern
Ireland peace talks Tuesday, the British government tried again to
discuss with the IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, to clarify
controversial conditions for Sinn Fein to join the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam admitted today in an
interview with BBC that her civil servants had contacted with Sinn
Fein by telephone and in writing on peace in the divided province.
</P>
<P>
She said the official talks with Sinn Fein, broken off after
IRA guerrillas killed two police officers in mid-June, were
resumed so that Sinn Fein could not blame Britain's ban on contact
for the IRA's refusal to end its war against British rule.
</P>
<P>
"(British Prime Minister) Tony Blair and I have made clear all
along that what's important is that Sinn Fein cannot give any
excuse that we have not clarified our position," she said.
</P>
<P>
But Mowlam said the renewed contacts were initiated by Sinn
Fein, which is demanding clarification on key issues as a
precondition for seeking a new IRA cease-fire which would admit the
party to the negotiations slated for September.
</P>
<P>
The British government said Sinn Fein could be admitted into
the multi-party peace talks only after the IRA announces a
cease-fire before or during the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein argues the surrender of guerrilla weapons should be
the last item on the agenda of the talks but Britain and Ireland
say they should hand over some weapons as the talks progress to
show good faith and build confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
