<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Israel-Palestinian Talks on Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) reached an agreement today on the taking-off and
landing procedures in the Dahaniya airport in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The progress in the aviation talks was achieved in the talks
held in Gaza between Fayed Zidan, Director-General of the PNA
Civil Aviation Authority, and Shaul Mofaz, head of Israeli Army
Planning Branch.
</P>
<P>
Sidan said the two sides also agreed on naming the Dahaniya
airport as Gaza International Airport. Moreover, Israel agreed to
let the PNA to hold the observer status in the International
Aviation Organization.
</P>
<P>
The agreements sparked optimism for the prospects of resuming
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations that have been frozen
since March when Israel began building the Har Homa settlement
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a move to calm down the tension caused by the continued
violent clashes in the Palestinian territories, Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai met with PNA Planning Minister Nabil
Shaath last week, during which the two agreed on expediting
the Dahaniya airport and on further construction of the Gaza
seaport.
</P>
<P>
Progress was also reported on resolving the differences on
opening "safe passages" for Palestinians traveling between the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The latest aviation agreements could pave the way for further
thawing of the Israeli-Palestinian ice in the peace negotiations
despite the violence in Hebron and other cities.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has said that the Dahaniya airport and Gaza seaport may
free the fledgling Palestinian economy from dependence on Israel
and enable the PNA to control its international trade.
</P>
<P>
But Israel insists that it should have security control over
the transportation in the airport and seaport because it fears
that the PNA could use the freedom of transport to smuggle in
advanced weapons that will threaten Israel's security. Until now,
the two sides have yet settled the disputes over the security
checks, and more talks are expected to follow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
