<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Critical for Trade: UNCTAD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) today urged Africa's decision
makers to take advantage of the latest technological development
to boost international trade.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD official Christine Cattell told delegates at the Second
Eastern and Southern Africa Trade Point meeting here that the
globalization and liberalization of world markets offer great
potential for the development and integration of the continent.
</P>
<P>
"If Africa is to increase its participation in international
trade, access to on-line trade and investment information are
very essential," Cattell told representatives from Kenya,
Botswana, Malawi, Mozambique, Mauritius, Namibia, Swaziland,
Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she stressed that "in a world of rapidly evolving
technology, training of human resources is a necessity."
</P>
<P>
"Trade point meetings are important to help strengthen the
trade point network in Africa by promoting regional cooperation
and mutual assistance," the UNCTAD official added.
</P>
<P>
A trade point is a center where trade information is available
for exporters, importers and the business community to develop
and expand international markets for their products.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD introduced a trade point program in 1992 to assist
countries in setting up such points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
