<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Demands Returning Arab Lands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli opposition leader said
today that Israel's security needs should not be based on
continued occupation of Arab lands, and pledged his support to the
establishment of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai Braon, leader of the Islaeli Peace Now Movement who
was visiting here heading a delegation, made the statement after
talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Meeting reporters after emerging from the talks, Braon held
Israel's Likud-led government responsible for the stalemate facing
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the ongoing policies adopted by Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu leaves no reason for optimism about a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
"It (the Netanyahu government) fails to carry on the
breakthrough realized in Rabin and Peres' era," he said, adding
that his party is mobilizing the Israeli public opinion to push
for early elections of "a new cabinet that will work for peace."
</P>
<P>
The movement believes in the necessity of realizing just and
balanced settlement through full participation by both
Palestinians and Israelis in everything and in all rights, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians should have their own state like Israel and
have their homeland where they can stay," he said. "Jerusalem
should be an undivided open city but also the capital of the
future Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government rejects the establishment of a full
independent Palestinian state and insists on keeping Jerusalem its
undivided capital.
</P>
<P>
As regard to Syria, Braon said that the only way for Israel to
realize peace is its complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights
and returning it back to Syria.
</P>
<P>
"Peace can never be realized without Syria which cannot accept
something less than what Egypt had accepted, namely return to the
international borders of 1967," he added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also refused to hand over Golan to Syria in return
for a peace treaty, something his predecessors had verbally
accepted. Peace talks with Syria have been frozen over one year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stepped in as the main mediator between the
Palestinians and Israelis in the past few weeks after U.S. efforts
failed to bring the two sides back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
But it apparently fell short of reviving the peace process
that collapsed in March when Israel broke ground for a new Jewish
settlement in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
