<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Resumes Peace Talks with Tribal Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government resumed
talks with the leaders of tribal insurgents here today in a bid to
establish a durable peace in the insurgency-torn southern
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT).
</P>
<P>
It is the fifth round of talks under the government of Sheikh
Hasina. The duration of the parley is not decided yet. However,
today's talks began in a "cordial" atmosphere, said an official
handout.
</P>
<P>
Chief Whip Hasnat Abdullah is leading the government side to
the meeting while the tribal delegation is headed by Shantu Larma
of the Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), the
political wing of the armed Shantibahini.
</P>
<P>
During the last peace talks on May 11, the government and the
PCJSS declared in a joint statement that they had reached an
agreement on the conflict and they would sign a peace treaty soon.
</P>
<P>
But the peace process received a severe jolt when differences
of opinion surfaced among the top leadership of the PCJSS, which
has struggled for about two decades for self-rule in the
resources-rich CHT.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Shantu Larma, chief of the PCJSS, was
facing severe opposition from a hard-liners' group against his
stand. Shantu is favoring a solution which will give up the
PCJSS's long-standing demand for autonomy in the CHT.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a team of the Refugee Welfare Association based in
Tripura of India recently visited Chittagong district to see
whether the repatriation process was going on in accordance with
the government's commitment.
</P>
<P>
More than 6000 refugees, out of a total of 40,000 tribal
refugees who fled away to India, returned home between March and
April this year on an "experimental basis," but members of 170
families have not yet been rehabilitated in their homesteads,
refugee leaders claimed.
</P>
<P>
The team said it was not satisfied with the repatriation
process and urged the government to start further repatriation
under the supervision of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Ministry of Special Affairs told reporters
that although both sides were keen to solve the problem, many
recent issues have made the situation complicated, "which made the
signing of a treaty unlikely in this round of talks," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
