<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Clamp Down on Govt Vehicle Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The provincial governments
of South Africa's nine provinces have started to clamp down on
officials found to be abusing government vehicles for private
business.
</P>
<P>
Provincial traffic officers will, from now on, be authorized
to demand permits from people driving government vehicles, said
an official.
</P>
<P>
Previously in South Africa, officials driving government
vehicles have only been subjected to internal fleet management
control systems that were not strictly implemented, said Butler
Matlapeng, spokesman for North West Provincial Transport and
Aviation Minister Frans Vilakazi.
</P>
<P>
Matlapeng said bureaucrats ran up hundreds of thousands of
kilometers for trips that could not be accounted for. This meant
provincial government departments incurred substantial losses in
petrol, repair and maintenance costs on unauthorized trips
undertaken by officials for private purpose.
</P>
<P>
Provinces such as North West and Kwazulu/Natal have now
employed special inspectors with powers to impound government
vehicles when found to be on the road without department permits.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in Gauteng Province, an economic power-house of the
country, the responsibility of monitoring government vehicles
will still fall into the hands of each department.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng's Public Transport and Roads Deputy Director Tobie
Roux said, however, it would be impossible for a team of
inspectors to monitor government vehicles here because of "unique
traffic patterns" and the large concentration of cars in the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
