<HEADLINE> Corrupt Egyptian Company Official Gets 10 Years in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A former chief of an Egyptian public
company was sentenced to a ten-year imprisonment term and a fine
of up to 26.762 million dollars today when found guilty of misuse
of power.
</P>
<P>
The Higher State Security Court handed out the verdict after
four months of deliberations over the corruption scandal, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Wahab Ahmed Al-Habbak, the convict, and members of his
family remained silent during the session.
</P>
<P>
Habbak, 61, former Board Chairman of the Holding Company for
Engineering Industries, was accused of using his influence to
amass personal wealth which was estimated at 50 million dollars
abroad.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested last year after the state surveillance
authorities discovered him making a big fortune out of illicit
business dealings. 
</P>
