<HEADLINE> Palestinian Police Deployed in Hebron to Prevent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 Palestinian police
and security personnel has been deployed along the line dividing
Palestinian self-rule areas from Jewish settlements in Hebron to
prevent further violence, the state-run Israel Radio reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Tarif Zayyad, Palestinian police commander in Hebron,
inspected the confrontation line this morning. He told reporters
that the Palestinian police had been deployed to ensure the area
not to be cut off from other parts of the Palestinian self-rule
city again.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli and Palestinian security officials met in Hebron
Sunday night to discuss the worsening situation in the city. The
Palestinian side agreed to make efforts to calm down the
mounting tensions, but at the same time, demanded that the
Israeli military authorities halt punitive measures against the
Palestinian residents in the city.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said that sanctions would be lifted when
change is seen in the field. And they agree to allow some
Palestinian shops to reopen. The stores, which had been ordered to
close by the army, located near an area from which shots were
fired and petrol bombs thrown at Israeli soldiers and Jewish
settlers.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of violence between Palestinians and Israeli
soldiers erupted after anti-Islamic posters were pasted on
Palestinian shops in the city. The insulting poster depicted
Prophet Muhammad as a pig.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has blamed the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) for encouraging the violence. Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu today threatened to take even harsh
measures against the Palestinians if violence continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
