<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Asia Up to 81 Bln Dlrs in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment into Asia
increased by 25 percent last year to 81 billion US dollars, with
China accounting for more than one half of these inflows,
according to figures published by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Citing a study by UNCTAD, the trade and development agency of
the UN, the Financial Times reported today that foreign direct
investment in developing countries rose from 97 billion US dollars
in 1995 to 129 billion US dollars last year, of which Asia
accounted for two-thirds, with China drawing 42 billion.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed China's success in drawing investment to
its large and growing domestic market, its economic "soft landing"
as well as measures to promote investment in interior provinces.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, of accounting for an increasing proportion of
foreign investment, Asia's developing countries have also become
important sources of capital.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 51 billion US dollars, or about 15 percent
of all the world's outward investment last year, came from
developing countries, with Asian developing countries accounting
for 46 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The study added that in addition to the increased capital
inflows into Asia, Latin American countries and the Caribbean also
saw a sharp rise in investment last year, 50 percent up on 1995 to
39 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Investment to UK Up to 32.8 Bln Dlrs in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain attracted 32.8 billion US
dollars of inward direct investment by European Union (EU)
countries last year, up from 22.8 billion in 1995, according to
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
The UK inflows accounted for 40 percent of all EU inward
investment and were more than double those into France, which
received 14.4 billion US dollars of EU investment last year, 1
billion more over 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to OECD data, Britain drew 81 billion dollar foreign
direct investment between 1991 and 1995, becoming the
third-largest host country in the world after the US and China.
</P>
<P>
The OECD said that much of the recent inward investment in
Britain took the form of mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
In the mean time, Britain was also the world's second-largest
source of outward foreign direct investment after the US last
year, with its outflows reaching a record 43.7 billion US dollars,
up from 42.7 billion in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
