<HEADLINE> Sudan's Government, Rebels to Negotiate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government and the
largest rebel group, the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA),
are scheduled to hold a new round of negotiations in August, the
independent Sudanese daily Alwan reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the Kenyan presidency has been trying
to make arrangements and hold contacts since the beginning of this
week with the mediator IGADD to set a date for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, no date has been fixed yet, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Inter-Government Authority for Drought and Development
(IGADD), which groups Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea,
Djibouti and Somali, has been trying to mediate an end to the
protracted civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted political sources as saying that the Kenyan
presidency will inform the Sudanese government and the rebel group
led by John Garang of the date of the negotiations as soon as it
completes contacts with the IGADD member states.
</P>
<P>
The same sources indicated that Garang has requested a delay of
the negotiations until October in a bid to win time to create
favorable military conditions that may boost his bargaining
position.
</P>
<P>
The sources further asserted that Sudan, having accepted
IGADD's principles of separating religion and politics and
instituting a multi-party system in Sudan, is determined to pursue
the peace process no matter the SPLA joins or not.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government signed a peace agreement with four
small southern rebel factions on April 21 in a bid to put an end
to the 13-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
However, the SPLA, the largest anti-government group operating
in southern Sudan, refused to sign the accord, creating
uncertainty over whether the peace can be holding.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's rebels in the south have fought the government since
1983, seeking a greater say in Sudan's affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
