<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Voices "Absolute Support" for Poland's EU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
expressed here today "absolute support" for Poland's bid to join
the European Union (EU), saying that "Poland is part of Europe.
Without Poland is the EU a torso."
</P>
<P>
Kohl made the remarks at a news conference after his meeting
with visiting Polish President Alexander Kwasniewski.
</P>
<P>
Kohl stopped short of naming any date for Poland's entry into
the EU, but he did stress that future EU members should be
admitted individually, not in groups. The admission of Austria,
Finland and Sweden to the EU as a group in 1996 should not serve
as a model for future enlargement, he added.
</P>
<P>
Poland was among the three Eastern European countries which
were invited last week to join the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO). The EU has yet to decide on candidates for
its own enlargement and is due to begin the new membership talks
next year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Kohl and Kwasniewski, who is accompanied by
other Polish leaders including Prime Minister Wlodzimierz
Cimoszewicz, was the inaugural session of planned regular
bilateral summits designed to promote relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders said that the current German-Polish ties are
better than any time in this century.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism of regular summits between German and Polish
leaders was initiated by Kohl during his visit to Warsaw in 1995.
Diplomats said Kohl wants to promote German-Polish ties in the
same manner which have boosted German-French ties since German
Chancellor Konrad Adenauer and French President Charles de Gaulle
started regular German-French summits in 1958.
</P>
<P>
French and German leaders now meet twice a year for regular
summits and there are also annual German-Italian and
German-Spanish summits.
</P>
<P>
According to Kohl, it has not been decided how often the
German-Polish summits are due to be held. But he said that the
next meeting will probably be held early next year in Warsaw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
