<HEADLINE> London Docklands Publishes 1996/97 Annual Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,200 new homes were sold
in London Docklands in 1996/97, the highest level since 1988 and
double the number of the previous year; 3,800 jobs were attracted
and 1.16 million sq. ft. of office space let.
</P>
<P>
In publishing the London Docklands Development Corporation's
(LDDC) 16th annual report today, Chairman Michael Pickard said, "With
just under a year to go, the LDDC's work to regenerate Docklands
is proceeding flat out. The last year saw every area of activity
move up a gear."
</P>
<P>
"Confidence is high and there is a great sense of optimism for
the future: more homes have been built and sold, nearly 4,000 jobs
created and more office space let. There is every indication that
the prospects look just as good for this year," the chairman
added.
</P>
<P>
The new Labor government's decision to press ahead with the
Millennium Exhibition Center is regarded as the best possible news
for the area and the company.
</P>
<P>
Together with the Jubilee Line Extension (underground) opening
in 1998, the program will secure the long-term future for the
people who live and work in London Docklands.
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the Partnership was also announced, which is
a local labor initiative designed to ensure that local residents
have the opportunity to work on the construction of the new
developments taking shape in the area and in the new jobs that
will be created as a result.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that in the next 18 months work will start on
nearly 1 billion pounds (1.6 billion US dollars) worth of new
development in London Docklands including the hotel, residential
and leisure scheme in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
