<HEADLINE> Greece: Madrid Communique Just Declaration of Principles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Greek-Turkish joint communique
issued last Tuesday in Madrid was just a declaration of principles
and its effectiveness depended on future action by the two
countries, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the communique was not an agreement but a joint
statement bearing the meaning of a non-aggression pact.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a climate of safety and stability in the
Aegean would depend on Ankara's future actions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The communique, which was signed between Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel and Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis while
attending the NATO summit in Madrid, called for respect for the
sovereignty of each country, international law and treaties as
well as resolution of disputes through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
In Greece, the cabinet unanimously endorsed the communique last
week, but 22 ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movements (PASOK)
deputies voiced their opposition to the communique.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that Athens was "gradually slipping into choices
that result in recognition of Ankara's claims, legalization of
Ankara's expansionistic status and an expiation of its policies."
</P>
<P>
Speaking in view of a PASOK Executive Bureau meeting on the
communique, Reppas said that party criticism of government actions
in relations with Turkey could create problems for the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
