<HEADLINE> Portugal, Angola to Promote Judicial Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Minister of Justice
Jose Vera Jardim said here today that Portugal wishes to
strengthen ties with Angola in the judicial field.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks to the press upon arriving at the local
airport.
</P>
<P>
Jardim, who is currently in Luanda to attend the fourth
meeting of judicial ministers from Portuguese-speaking countries,
said, long years of civil war has seriously damaged Angola's
legal machines, adding that Portugal believes legal machines and
judicial system are essential to the development of a nation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he noted, Portugal intends to cooperate with Angola
in rebuilding the latter's legal machines.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Angola, former colony of Portugal which
gained independence in 1975, the Portuguese minister will
exchange broadly with colleagues in Angola to make their
cooperation effective.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting to be held from July 15 to 18 has its
theme focusing on "Youth Crimes and Street Children", which,
Jardim said is a common issue plaguing the seven
Portuguese-Speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
It should become their joint action to fight against youth
crimes, Jardim stressed.
</P>
<P>
Arriving on the same plane with Jardim were judicial ministers
from Guinea-Bissau, Cape Verde and Brazil. The ministers of
Mozambique and Sao Tome and Principe are already in Luanda.
</P>
