<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aids Epidemic Critical in Botswana: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- With the figures which show
four percent of the population will have AIDS and 18 percent will
be HIV-infected by 2000, the AIDS epidemic in Botswana has
entered a critical stage, a senior government official said
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop held in Gaborone, Botswana, by the AIDS
unit of the Health Ministry, unit co-ordinator Rose Mandevu said
social and economic consequences would likely to deepen in the
next five years if nothing would be done to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
A report quoted Mandevu as saying the unit's plan to combat
HIV/AIDS over the next five years showed that of the 15 to 49
year-old most sexually active section of the population, 25
percent would be HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
She said the worst thing is that the most economically active
sectors of the population are most affected by the epidemic. In
Botswana people aged 15 to 49 accounted for 89 percent of all
reported cases, among which 56 percent were in the youth group
aged 15 to 29.
</P>
<P>
Early initiation of sex in Botswana increased exposure to HIV,
of all HIV cases reported in the 15- to 19-year age group between
1986 and the first quarter of 1996, 90 percent were of teenage
females, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
The first case of AIDS was confirmed in 1985 in Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Lack of women's empowerment against cultural and traditional
practices in sexual matters and relationships had been identified
as factors that made women more vulnerable to HIV infection, said
Mandevu.
</P>
<P>
From 1986 to 1996, women accounted for 68 percent of
infections in the 15- to 29-year age group, Mandevu said.
</P>
<P>
She also said the epidemic is expected to have significant
impact on the major gains made in the past two decades in
Botswana in the areas of child survival and mortality and life
expectancy.
</P>
<P>
Between 1971 and 1991, infant mortality rate per 1000 had
declined from 92 to 45, while life expectancy had increased from
55.5 to 61.7 years, said the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
