<HEADLINE> UN Calls for Increasing Role of Civilian Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today issued a presidential statement, calling for an increasing
role and special functions of civilian police in peacekeeping
operations.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the Security Council encouraged states to
make available to the United Nations at short notice appropriately
trained civilian police, if possible through the United Nations
stand-by agreements.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed the importance of the recruitment of
qualified civilian police from the widest possible geographic
range to serve in the United Nations operations. It also stressed
the importance of the recruitment of female police officers to the
United Nations operations.
</P>
<P>
The council underlined the necessity for the United Nations
civilian police to be trained as required to render assistance and
support in the organization, training and monitoring of national
police and to help defuse tension on the ground through
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated the need for close coordination between civilian
police and the military, humanitarian and other civilian
components of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has established and authorized a growing
number of peacekeeping operations which contain both civilian and
military components. Civilian police in peacekeeping operations
have been playing a more and more important role those years in
contributing to the building of confidence and security between
parties and among local populations, in order to prevent conflict
and contain conflict or to build peace in the aftermath of
conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
