<HEADLINE> Clinton's Advisory Board on Race Convenes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
advisory board on race agreed today that education should be a
high priority in the panel's year-long examination of the
country's racial problems.
</P>
<P>
At its first meeting, the seven-member panel, which was formed
more than a month ago, identified areas to explore along with
their relationship to Americans' racial views. Among them were
education, immigration, economic equity, criminal justice and
conditions in urban centers.
</P>
<P>
Board chairman John Hope Franklin warned members not to expect
sudden results or to feel intimidated by the grand scope of the
problems they will try to resolve.
</P>
<P>
Board members agreed that education is paramount, starting with
their mission to better educate Americans on race.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Clinton named the Education Department's top lawyer
Judith A. Winston executive director of the year-long effort.
Winston will work with Clinton, the board and the White House
staff to coordinate the campaign to educate the nation about race,
to promote a dialogue and develop solutions to help bridge the
nation's racial divide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
