<HEADLINE> New UNSCOM Chief Inspector to Visit Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The new U.N. chief inspector
on Iraq's weapons of mass destruction Richard Butler will be here
Friday to detail his policies on Iraq to Kuwaiti officials,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
An official from Kuwait Foreign Ministry said that Butler, who
succeeded Rolf Ekeus on July 1 and is on his first visit to
Kuwait, would hold talks with Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad
Al-Sabah, acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah
Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, parliament Speaker Ahmad Al-Saadoun
and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Sabah Al-Salem.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, He is expected to reassure the
Kuwaiti leadership of the continued determination of the
U.N. Special Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM) to obtain Iraq's
compliance with all U.N. resolutions related to its aggression on
Kuwait in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council has been continuing to oppose any
relaxation of sanctions until Iraq demonstrates its willingness
to fully comply with the resolutions, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq failed to grant UNSCOM inspectors immediate and
unconditional access to any location in its territories they
wished to examine in order to testify that Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction are thoroughly eliminated.
</P>
<P>
U.N. inspectors, comprising some 150 experts, are to check
that Iraq was not capable to produce long range missiles or
possess chemical weapons. 
</P>
