<HEADLINE> Turkey's Petrol Prices Rise 30 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's new coalition government
announced today a rise of more than 30 percent of gasoline prices,
the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkish State Minister Gunes Taner, who is in charge of the
economy, said the increase of consumption taxes on petroleum
products was fair, adding that those who are richer should pay
more for using more petrol.
</P>
<P>
"In a country like Turkey where income distribution is
unjust, the tax burden is generally carried by fixed income
earners," Taner said.
</P>
<P>
He said:" Oil consumption in Turkey has increased to 30
million tonnes. If you keep the oil prices too low it will
disturb the balances and bring a new burden on public finances."
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that the government has no intention to
increase petrol prices again except in the case of change in
world oil prices or the Turkish Lira's exchange value.
</P>
<P>
The new government has said that it was forced to raise the
petrol prices because it inherited a troubled economy with
inflation running at near 80 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
"Immediate measures must be taken to lower inflation.
Otherwise, we will be likely to have an inflation rate of 150
percent in 1998", Taner claimed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
