<HEADLINE> EC Expects Sustained Growth in Central Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC), the
European Union's executive body, said in a publication that it
expected sustained economic growth in Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EC made the remark against the backdrop that the economic
slowdown in Western Europe has had a negative impact on economic
growth in Central European countries (CECs) in 1996, though the
impact remained limited in most countries.
</P>
<P>
In the publication, Economic Reform Monitor, the EC noted that
in 1997 and 1998, growth is expected to accelerate again as the
CECs should be able to benefit from the anticipated faster
recovery in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EC explained that external deficits in CECs are rising
rapidly since imports are rising fast while export growth is
constrained by foreign demand. Economic growth is now mainly
driven by domestic demand, it added.
</P>
<P>
The total trade deficit of the CECs now represents some 7.5
percent of the region's GDP, according to the EC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
