<HEADLINE> Crime, Corruption Could Wreck S. Africa: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's democracy
could collapse if the corruption of the police and the judicial
system by organized crime syndicates was not stopped, Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki warned here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the weekend meeting of the
National Executive Committee (NEC), highest policy-making body of
the African National Congress (ANC), Mbeki said elements of the
previous apartheid government's security forces were also
contributing to the crime problem for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said: "It is quite clear that if the corruption in the
police, the judicial system, the prisons service and at the
Department of Home Affairs is not stopped, you could have a
collapse of the entire democratic system."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ANC's Acting Secretary-General Cheryl Carolus said
the NEC meeting noted and expressed serious concern about
evidence that elements from the old state security machinery were
involved in drug dealing, money laundering, car hijacking, taxi
violence and in organized crime syndicates.
</P>
<P>
"Some of these appear to be deliberately engineered and
politically motivated criminal actions," said Carolus.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also stressed that crime had political consequences,
adding commercial crime such as evading import border controls
and theft of containers affected people wanting to trade with
South Africa. 
</P>
