<HEADLINE> US Announces More Food Aid for DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
today that it will provide 27 million dollars more in food aid for
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) as a response to
the latest appeal from the U.N. World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
"In response to the World Food Program's announcement July 9 of
an expanded appeal for humanitarian food aid for children in North
Korea, the United States government has decided to extend 100,000
metric tons of grain valued at approximately 27 million dollars,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The allocation of the food will be monitored by the World Food
Program and U.S. private and voluntary organizations, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"Forty-five thousand tons of grain will be monitored
exclusively by the World Food Program and used to feed children of
age 6 and under, in nurseries, kindergartens, and orphanages," he
said. "The distribution of the other 55,000 tons will be monitored
by a variety of U.S. private and voluntary organizations, who will
work in conjunction with the World Food Program."
</P>
<P>
Burns emphasized the aid will be directed at the most
vulnerable -- chiefly children, but also elderly population in the
DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Burns denied there is any links between the U.S. food aid and
its political talks with the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"We have never linked food assistance to the political talks,"
he said. "We have great respect for the World Food Program. They
issued an urgent appeal for food because children and the elderly
are experiencing famine. And we felt... that we had to step up to
the plate and deliver." 
</P>
</TEXT>
