<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Ready to Talk with Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government said
today that it is ready to pursue negotiations with the rebel
faction headed by John Garang to end the 13-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today before the Sudanese National Assembly, Foreign
Minister Ali Osman Mohamed Taha said the resumption of
negotiations with Garang would not affect the implementation of
the Khartoum peace agreement the government reached with four
small rebel groups in April.
</P>
<P>
The four small groups, along with the Garang-led Sudan People's
Liberation Army, the largest group, were fighting the government
in southern Sudan to seek a greater say in the country's affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Khartoum agreement, in which the Garang faction refused to
join, stipulates a referendum for people in south Sudan to decide
whether they would stay in or out of the country after a four-year
transitional period.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to push forward the peace march, the accord and its
implementation will be included in a constitutional decree drafted
by the Justice Ministry, which is expected to take effect upon the
approval by the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Osman said President Omar Bashir would ask the National
Assembly to hold an emergency session to sanction the 14th
constitutional decree. After its passage, a coordination council
with both government and anti-government representatives will be
formed to take charge of affairs in southern Sudan in the next
four years before a plebiscite is held there for people to opt
between unity and secession.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the government and the Garang faction are
to take place in August under the auspices of the Inter-government
Authority for Drought and Development (IGADD).
</P>
<P>
The IGADD, which groups Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia,
Eritrea, Djibouti and Somali, has been trying to mediate a
settlement of the Sudan issue.
</P>
<P>
It issued a declaration of principles in 1994 calling for
separation of religion and politics and institution of a
multi-party system in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese foreign minister told the National Assembly that
the government had rejected the declaration "because it entailed
conditions and issues that touch on the unity of Sudan."
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Sudanese delegation to the recent IGADD
summit in Nairobi accepted it only "as an agenda" for renewed
negotiations with Garang. "It is not binding to Sudan," he added.
</P>
<P>
Osman also said that the Khartoum peace agreement had decided
the issue of self-determination as well as other points of
difference to be negotiated with Garang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
