<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calm Resumes After Fighting in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 14 (Xinhua) - All is quiet in Jui of the
eastern side of the capital after clashes between Sierra Leone
army and a contingent of Nigerian forces serving in the west
African Peace-keeping Forces (ECOMOG) over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The over 20-hour-long fighting which started on Saturday
afternoon, has left more than 30 civilians dead and about 50
seriously wounded, doctors at local hospitals said here today.
</P>
<P>
State television carried pictures on Sunday night of the
destruction and the bodies of a family of four killed in a bomb
blast from a Nigerian air force jet flying over the area.
</P>
<P>
The jet was sent when both sides used artillery and other
heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
A field visit to the area of Jui, 17 miles from the capital on
Sunday and early today by this Xinhua reporter showed that the
area has been completely devastated with many residents
abandoning their homes with bundles and mats for the capital.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides were dug in with trenches facing each other and
there are certain to be further clashes if the momentum
continues," he said.
</P>
<P>
A doctor at the central hospital said that 15 corpses of
civilians were now at the mortuary while the surgeon in charge of
the military hospital disclosed that 15 more bodies have also
been brought in.
</P>
<P>
"The bodies were completely mangled and hardly recognizable,"
said the surgeon.
</P>
<P>
Red cross officials are still searching for more bodies which
they believe would have been buried as a result of the
bombardment.
</P>
<P>
Traffic between the capital and the interior is still
disrupted. But a senior military official assured it would
resume by midday.
</P>
<P>
About 10 Nigerians died in the fighting while the Sierra Leone
army said it lost five with 12 wounded.
</P>
<P>
There has not been any confirmation of the figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
