<HEADLINE> UN Extends Mandate of UN Military Observers in Prevlaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today decided to extend the mandate of the United Nations military
observers in Prevlaka Peninsula for another six months until
January 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution, the Security Council once again reaffirmed
its commitment to the independence, sovereignty and territorial
integrity of the Republic of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern over that the parties had failed to make any
progress in adopting the practical options proposed by the United
Nations military observers in May 1996 to reduce tension and
improve safety and security in the area, the Security Council
called on the parties to abide by their mutual commitment fully
implementing the 1996 Agreement on Normalization of Relations
between the Republic of Croatia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Council urged the parties to cease all the violations of
the demilitarization regime and military or other activities which
may increase tension, and cooperate fully with the United Nations
military observers and ensure their safety and freedom of
movement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
