<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Involvement in Bombing in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department today
said that there is no evidence that Americans were behind the
bombing of two hotels in Cuba's capital of Havana this weekend.
</P>
<P>
"There's no evidence whatsoever that Americans were behind it,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters. "And
needless to say, the United States government had absolutely
nothing to do with this."
</P>
<P>
Two Cubans were slightly injured in the two explosions, which
took place on Saturday at the Hotel National and the Hotel Capri
in Havana. Cuba has charged that the U.S. government is behind
it.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's Interior Ministry said in a statement on Saturday that
it had evidence that the "people responsible for these deeds and
also the materials they used came from the United States."
</P>
<P>
Burns asked the Cuban government to turn over any evidence it
has that Americans were involved in bombing.
</P>
<P>
"We have no information whatsoever here in Washington or
Havana, in our interest section, about the origin of these
explosions...We know nothing about them," he added.
</P>
<P>
"If there's any information the Cuban government has that they
think is real, and they want to turn it over to us, if they think
Americans are implicated, we will listen," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
