<HEADLINE> First World Food Program For Southwest Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) and
the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) will
join hands to help Sichuan province and Chongqing Municipality in
a poverty alleviation program over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was signed in Beijing today by Else Larsen,
country director, and Jia Jiansan, deputy director-general of the
International Cooperation Department of China's Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the WFP will provide the southwest
China province and Chongqing Municipality with food worth 19
million US dollars, and IFAD will provide them with 22.65 million
US dollars in low-interest loans.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,000 small and medium-sized agriculture, forestry
and infrastructure projects will be built in eight specially
designated poor counties in Sichuan and Chongqing. More than
907,000 poverty-stricken farmers are expected to benefit from the
project.
</P>
<P>
It is specifically designed to help women. Some 430,000 women
are expected to increase their economic leverage as well as their
ability to make decisions on household affairs by taking part in
small scale production and processing industries.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has been providing food assistance to China since
1979. It has provided 750 million US dollars worth of food to
China, which has bee used to help 22 million poor farmers and
herdsmen in 181 counties and cities over the past 17 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
