<HEADLINE> Former Polish Coach Takes Over Shanghai Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Andrej Strejlau, former head
coach for the Polish national soccer team, took over the coaching
post of Chinese Professional League side Shanghai Shenhua on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Strejlau, 57, trained the Polish national eleven for 54
international matches from 1989 to 1993. He had been Shenhua's
advisor since April.
</P>
<P>
He replaced Bulgarian-born Stojkov, who resigned on Sunday
night after Shanghai was drawn 0-0 by Guangzhou Apollo in a home
match on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Stojkov, who had coached the team for eight months, said he
could not stand the fierce competition in the league and "asked
for a refreshing leave", the club said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said his psychological burden was too heavy to bear, the
club added.
</P>
<P>
Shenhua, who won the league in 1995, is now second behind
Dalian Wanda on the 12-team league standings.
</P>
<P>
The club said Stojkov remains in the club as an advisor for the
rest of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
