<HEADLINE> China Points To Victory In Anti-Smuggling Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Li Lanqing, speaking
at a national meeting on anti-smuggling work today in Beijing,
said that China has had some achievements in its anti-smuggling
campaign, especially in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
From January of last year to June this year, a total of 20,908
smuggling cases were uncovered, involving more than 15 billion
yuan (some 1.8 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
But, Li pointed out, in spite of the success, the situation is
still serious and police must prepare for a crackdown in the
second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Attention should be paid to the seizure of some major items
like petroleum products, he said, and local officials must be
fully aware of the harmful nature of smuggling and must look after
the nation's interests instead of their own.
</P>
<P>
This is not only an economic campaign, he explained, but a
political one as well, because it is part of the anti-corruption
program and of developing the Party.
</P>
<P>
Because a few state-owned enterprises, collective firms, and
foreign-backed companies have been involved in the smuggling, big
cases must be investigated very thoroughly, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
