<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Probe Nazi Gold Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's central bank is launching
an investigation into whether it was involved in transactions
dealing with looted Nazi gold, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Canada has started reviewing its records to verify
information in a newly declassified U.S. intelligence document.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure you we will be pursuing our review quickly and
thoroughly so the situation can be clarified as soon as possible,"
the bank's governor Gordon Thiessen said in a letter to the
Canadian Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
"We share your concern that the gold of other central banks
held for safekeeping in Canada could have been associated in any
way, however indirectly, with Nazi Germany gold transactions," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. document dated September 10, 1944, and released last
week said Portugal used the Swiss National Bank to swap 20 tons of
looted Nazi gold for gold held in the Bank of Canada and the
U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
In 1942, the Bank of Portugal deposited about four tons of gold
it bought from Nazi Germany in its account with the Swiss National
Bank, the document said.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss transferred the same amount of gold in a Bank of
Canada account to the Portuguese, who in turn transferred the
title to the gold into its Swiss account.
</P>
<P>
In 1944, the Swiss and Portuguese swapped another 15 tons of
Nazi gold for gold held in the U.S. Federal Reserve Bank, the
document said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing To Promote Primary Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will develop a series of
regulations to promote education in local primary and middle
schools, according to Tao Chunhui, a senior education official
from the Beijing Education Commission (BEC).
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference in Beijing today that the BEC will
set up a new education system that provides students with a
diversity of courses instead of just tests and exams.
</P>
<P>
School-age children can attend primary and middle schools near
their homes directly without any enrollment exams in 1998, Tao
noted. Those who want to receive further education can apply to
colleges and universities on their own without the approval of
local middle schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, education departments will make a joint
effort to compile new textbooks and teaching materials for primary
education, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The BEC will also set up more primary and middle schools in
rural areas and training programs for teachers, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
