<HEADLINE> Pipeline For Transporting Northwest China's Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A pipeline to move crude oil out of
the Tarim Basin in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region went into operation today.
</P>
<P>
The 476-kilometer pipeline connects the city of Korla in the
west, which is a major oil production base, and the Shanshan
Oilfield in the east. It can handle five million to 10 million
tons of oil annually.
</P>
<P>
It is the first section of a much long line that will
ultimately go to Sichuan and Henan provinces, and is important
because scientists have found a dozen oil and natural gasfields in
the Tarim Basin and nearby regions, with 500 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Some eight million tons of crude oil are expected to be pumped
out by the end of the century, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
