<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Members Grill Finance Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait' parliament today
interpellated Deputy Prime Minister and Financial Minister Naser
Al-Roudhan over alleged mismanagement, irregularities in handling
public funds and negligence.
</P>
<P>
The questioning motion was initiated by liberal members of the
National Assembly, which decided on July 8 to interpellate the
minister, who chairs the Kuwait Investment Authority which manages
the state's foreign investments of about 40 billion U.S. dollars,
the Central Bank and the Kuwait Airways.
</P>
<P>
Three parliament members today grilled the minister over his
failure to retrieve a sum of 25 million dollars deposited in a
"Tunisian bank suffering financial problems."
</P>
<P>
They accused him of lingering in the application of a certain
law related to the use of empty land plots, squandering huge sums
of public funds.
</P>
<P>
The minister was "reluctant to implement several important laws
directly related to public interests," they said. They also
questioned the standards and criteria adopted by the minister in
nominating chairmen and directors of state-owned institutions.
</P>
<P>
However, Acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah said earlier this month
that the cabinet was keen on supporting Al-Roudhan in the
parliament interrogation motion.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah praised Al-Roudhan's contributions to Kuwait's
post-war economic recovery and development, adding the questioning
was nothing more than the exercise of a constitutional right.
</P>
<P>
Twenty four lawmakers have filed 12 grilling motions against
government members in the history of Kuwait's democratic life
which began with the first legislative session in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The right has been practiced in Kuwait's previous parliaments
and has for once forced a minister to resign in 1985. This
questioning was the first since the election of the current
parliament in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Al-Roudhan said last Wednesday he would stick to the truth if
he were challenged in parliament over his supervision of key
economic bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
