<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets With Vietnamese Party Leader (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng, meeting today
with Do Muoi, general secretary of the Vietnamese Communist Party
(VCP) Central Committee, said that the two countries' leaders have
met several times since Do Muoi visited China in November 1995 and
these have played an important role in the development of
relations between the two parties and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that official talks between Jiang Zemin and Do Muoi on
Monday were "rich in content" and had "profound significance" for
the future development of relations and that promoting the
expansion of friendship and cooperation between the two countries
is not only in the basic interests of the two peoples, but also
benefits peace and stability in the region and the world as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China and Vietnam are good neighbors with a
common border and common interests in many areas like politics and
the economy and that "We are ready to join efforts with the
Vietnamese side to expand relations in all aspects and to properly
resolve problems in bilateral relations that remain as soon as
possible to push Sino-Vietnamese friendship and co-operation to a
higher developmental level."
</P>
<P>
He said that China will stick to its independent foreign policy
of peace, maintain good-neighborly relations with neighboring
countries, and never seek influence in political or economic
spheres.
</P>
<P>
Its principle is equality and mutual benefit, he noted, and the
two sides should take their needs and their practicality into
consideration and should increase co-operation, standardize deals,
adopt successful international practices, and reform old customs.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to provide a certain amount of free aid to
Vietnam in so far as it can, though the amount will not be large,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises will be the major means of cooperation and the
Chinese government will support and guide them in taking part in
competition in Vietnam on an equal footing with others, he said,
adding that the Sino-Vietnamese Joint Committee on Economic
Cooperation will play a bigger role in this regard.
</P>
</TEXT>
