<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Says Film Business Should Develop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng, during a
visit to the Lucky Film Corporation in Hebei province's Baoding
yesterday, said that the country's film business should develop
more, and that the company should make a greater contribution by
adapting to the market.
</P>
<P>
Lucky is a key state-owned producer of film that has broken the
monopoly of foreign companies like Fuji and Kodak, and has a big
share of the domestic market. Its color film is sold in more than
40 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the central government has a policy of developing
the country's photo-sensitive paper industry with imported
technology and capital, and by setting up joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
It has also decided to adopt preferential policies to
encourage the development of Lucky's products.
</P>
<P>
In drawing up production plans, he said, Lucky should be
market-oriented and should pay attention to efficiency and respond
to market demands. The success of an enterprise is mainly the
result of the exploration and response to the market by making
products appealing to consumers, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Li on the inspection tour were vice-premier Wu
Bangguo and other senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
