<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Damaged Chinese Railway Resumes Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A railway that suspended
operations for 106 hours because of floods in east China's Fujian
province resumed operation this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The railway, linking Yingtan city in Jiangxi province with
Xiamen city in Fujian, was damaged by landslides caused by floods
during a period of continuous downpours this month.
</P>
<P>
An 80-m stretch of track was left up in the air when 30,000
cubic meters of earth slid out from under it, forcing the railway
to shut down operations the morning of July 11.
</P>
<P>
It took four days for some 1,000 railway workers and PLA
soldiers to repair the roadbed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
