<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Forest Commemorates Ming Dynasty General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A stone forest has been built here
to mark the 335th anniversary of the recovery of Taiwan by Zheng
Chenggong, a general of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
Some 600 people from China's inland areas, Hong Kong and Taiwan
attended today's opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The 3,000-sq.m. forest was built alongside a memorial hall for
Zheng in his hometown of Nanan in Quanzhou city in Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
The stone tablets in the forest are 1.6 m by 0.62 m to
commemorate the year 1662 when Zheng took Taiwan from Dutch
colonialists. They mostly contain inscriptions of prominent
people. Seven of them use Zheng's handwriting.
</P>
<P>
Zheng refused to be ruled by the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) and
led a group of men across the Taiwan Straits in 1661 and got
control of the island the following year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Police Arrest 4 Murderers of Japanese Monk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Four of the six masked
assailants involved in the murder of Japanese Buddhist Yunataka
Nawatame have been arrested, Nepali police announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Inspector General of Nepali Police Dhurba Bahadur Pradhan told
a press conference that the four were netted Monday, and a massive
hunt is being launched to trace the other two who are still at
large.
</P>
<P>
Investigations found that the assailants had plotted to rob
Buddhist Nawatame of his money since June 27, Pradhan said.
</P>
<P>
They thought the Japanese monk involved in the construction of
the World Peace Stupa at Lumbini must have a large amount of
foreign currency, Pradhan said.
</P>
<P>
They sneaked into the monk's house on the night of July 3. But
Nawatame turned down their demand for money, so they shot him in
the neck, the police chief added.
</P>
<P>
Nawatame's death in Lumbini, the birthplace of Lord Buddha in
southern Nepal, has spelled a wave of condemnation across the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Committed to Negotiated Peace in Region: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said here today that his country "is fully committed to the
negotiated peace and settlement of issues in South Asia".
</P>
<P>
"However, our national security and settlement of Jammu and
Kashmir issue -- acceptable to Pakistan and Kashmiris -- are vital
for us," Sharif said while talking to visiting U.S. General Joseph
W. Ralston.
</P>
<P>
Ralston, vice chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, is
heading a four-member delegation on a three-day visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two discussed the regional situation,
particularly Pakistan's initiative to resume talks with India with
the aim of finding peaceful and negotiated settlement of issues.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister also urged the U.S. delegation to
find ways for further improving the forward movement on bilateral
issues between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
