<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With Vietnamese Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo
met with his Vietnamese counterpart Phan Van Khai here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The two vice-premiers exchanged views on furthering bilateral
economic and trade ties during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who is also a member of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), said that the
frequent exchange of visits by the leaders of the two countries in
the past few years has given important impetus to Sino-Vietnamese
economic ties. The trade volume between the two countries has
increased year after year thanks to the joint efforts of the two
sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
China and Vietnam, linked by mountains and rivers, have similar
national conditions, Wu continued, noting that the two countries
enjoy a good political relationship and their economies are
complimentary, which provide good conditions and big potential for
bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The CPC and the Chinese government place importance to
Sino-Vietnamese economic ties, Wu said. He expressed the belief
that the current China tour by Do Muoi, General Secretary of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of Viet Nam (CPV), would
open broader prospects for various forms of Sino-Vietnamese
economic and trade cooperation on the basis of equality and
mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Phan, who is also member of the Political Bureau of CPV Central
Committee and is accompanying Do Muoi on his current China visit,
said that Do Muoi's visit would push forward Vietnam-China ties in
an all-round way and promote an early settlement of the left-over
problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese deputy prime minister expressed his hope that
the two countries would adopt practical measures to make bilateral
cooperation in economy, science and technology more fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Minister Liu Jiang of Agriculture briefed Do Muoi on
the development of China's agriculture this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese entrepreneurs also held talks with their
Vietnamese counterparts this afternoon to explore the
possibilities of expanding bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
