<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Hoping for Cooler Weather (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Basically this phenomenon is natural, but such human
activities as the concentration of large numbers of people in the
city area certainly have some influence on the high temperatures,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the State Meteorology Bureau also say that since
late June, most parts of north China have experienced hot weather,
with the average highs being two to four degrees more than in
normal years.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Beijing Meteorological Observatory say that
this century similar phenomena have occurred several times, but
this will probably be the longest.
</P>
<P>
Although complaints can be heard almost everywhere, doctors
working in emergency wards are not much busier than usual. "Due to
various heatstroke prevention actions the number of patients have
not increased dramatically," said one doctor at Union Hospital.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say, the hot-weather will probably affect
grain output in the fall in north China, especially corn and
soybeans, and will very likely be followed by rainstorms. 
</P>
