<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Hoping for Cooler Weather (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Eight extremely hot days have
caused the people of Beijing to pay more attention to the weather
than at any other time.
</P>
<P>
People gazed expectantly when dark clouds occasionly appeared
in the sky, but the clouds always drifted away, leaving the heat
waves and sighs of disappointment immediately after they had
concluded celebrations of the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Although cool rain is expected to be moving in gradually from
south China, there is little hope for the next two or three days
that the city's people will hear any good news from the weather
bureau.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Beijing Meteorological Observatory say that,
since July 8th, the daily highs in Beijing have been above 35
degrees C. The hottest was on July 13th, when temperatures over
most of the city were above 38 degrees, and the reading in the
Shijingshan District was 39.8.
</P>
<P>
"Having had two cool summers in 1995 and 1996, Beijingers will
complain more about the hot weather," said Lei Zhenfa, director of
the Beijing Meteorological Observatory.
</P>
<P>
Out on the streets, there are fewer pedestrians and bicycles
than usual, while people crowd into shops and department stores
with air-conditioning not only to shop but also to enjoy the cool.
</P>
<P>
At a Baishiqiao intersection, a traffic policeman said that
people are staying in their offices longer to avoid the sunlight,
so afternoon rush hour has moved from about 5:00 p.m. to after
6:00.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang Chaoying, a senior expert from the State
Metoerology Bureau, the main cause of this year's sustained hot
weather is a strong pressure-ridge over the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
