<HEADLINE> Romanian Police Seize Big Heroin Haul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Romanian police seized some 83
kilograms of heroin from a truck in the capital on Monday, their
biggest haul so far this year, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Police, who searched the truck after a tip-off, also found more
than 20 kilograms of explosives in the vehicle owned by a Turkish
company. They also detained four people suspected of drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the four people, including a Romanian and
foreigners, are suspected of belonging to an international drug
cartel and were involved in drug trafficking under the cover of
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Romania has become a key staging post for European
drug-traffickers since 1991. Drugs from the Middle East, Asia and
Latin America are increasingly being smuggled to other European
countries via the central European nation.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, only 35 kilograms of drugs were seized but in 1996 5.7
tons of drug were seized. Some 1.4 tons of drugs have been seized
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
A tenth of the drugs smuggled into Romania are sold in the
country to a growing number of drug addicts, mainly youngsters,
the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Central Bank Reduces Liquidity Ratio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
has reduced the liquidity ratio requirements for commercial
banks from 25 percent to 20 percent, according to a statement
from the bank today.
</P>
<P>
The move will make banks and non-bank financial bodies in
Kenya have more resources available for lending, thus
encouraging them to lower their base lending rates, said the
statement made by Reuben Marambi, the chief CBK banking manager.
</P>
<P>
CBK has demanded all banks and non-banking
institutions to maintain a certain percentage of their assets
in liquid form to facilitate day-to-day business.
</P>
<P>
CBK also requested financial institutions as from August 1
to declare a specific base lending rate.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of CBK's efforts to restructure domestic
debt from the short-dated Treasury bills to long-term bonds and
governmental stocks, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The bank's fourth issue of floating rate Treasury bonds which
have a much higher yield than the 91-day Treasury bills started
trading last week at the secondary market.
</P>
<P>
Yields on the 91-day bills for the first time this year fell
to under 20 percent last month. Now they stand at 18.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates on loans in the eastern African country
have been the subject of debate with investors saying they are a
hindrance to economic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
