<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets With Laotian Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Sino-Lao political, military,
economic, cultural, and educational exchanges and cooperation have
had some results in recent years, Chinese Premier Li Peng said
here today.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with the Laotian Deputy Prime Minister Boungnhang
Vorachith this afternoon, Li said that the two countries have
successfully resolved their historical boundary issue and the
border area has become a peaceful, friendly and cooperative one.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Laos have collaborated with each other in
international and regional affairs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the Lao government has always stuck to the "one
China" stand and has supported the Chinese people's peaceful
reunification cause. And Laotian party and state leaders have sent
warm congratulatory messages to the Chinese government on the
resumption of its sovereignty over Hong Kong, he said, thanking
Laos for this.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade co-operation between the two countries have
made tremendous progress, with the range of goods expanding and
trade volume increasing every year. "The Chinese government is
willing, on the basis of equality and mutual benefit, to increase
economic and trade co-operation in order to add substantive
content to the bilateral good-neighborly and friendly relations,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has a good-neighborly friendship policy and
attaches great importance to establishing a long-term and stable
friendly relationship with the countries of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Boungnhang Vorachith said the Laos-China
relationship is developing smoothly, and his talks with
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing this morning were fruitful.
</P>
<P>
He said the concrete projects involved in the bilateral
economic and trade cooperation will continue to be negotiated and
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Present at today's meeting were Vice-Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan and Vice-Minister Liu Shanzai of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Boungnhang began his visit in Kunming, capital of southwest
China's Yunnan Province on July 13. He is here at the invitation
of Li Lanqing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
