<HEADLINE> HK Regional Affairs Advisors Complete Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony was held here today
to mark the end of term for the Hong Kong Regional Affairs
Advisors engaged by the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, held in the China Resources Building, was
attended by Qin Wenjun, vice director of the Xinhua News Agency
Hong Kong Branch, and nearly 200 Regional Affairs Advisors from
Kowloon area.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on behalf of Zhou Nan, director of the Xinhua Hong
Kong Branch, Qin said that all the Regional Affairs Advisors have
done a lot of work for and made significant contributions to the
smooth transition of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"You have won the people's respect and your names will be
recorded in history," he said.
</P>
<P>
Between March 1994 and July 1995, the Xinhua News Agency Hong
Kong Branch engaged a total of 670 Hong Kong residents from
various social circles as Hong Kong Regional Affairs Advisors.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important measure to ensure Hong Kong's smooth
transition and to implement the principle of 'one country, two
systems' and 'Hong Kong people administering Hong Kong' with a
high degree of autonomy," Qin noted.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the Branch has attached great importance
to the role of the advisors, and has kept close contact with them.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, he said, various offices of the Xinhua
Branch across Hong Kong invited the advisors to more than 440
panel discussions and consultative conferences on Hong Kong
regional affairs, and solicited individual opinions from the
advisors frequently.
</P>
<P>
"Though your term has come to an end, we hope that you will
continue to be concerned about the regional affairs of Hong Kong,
and support the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region," he added.
</P>
<P>
A similar ceremony was held Monday for 192 Regional Affairs
Advisors from Hong Kong Island area. It was attended by vice
director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch Zhang
Junsheng.
</P>
<P>
Another ceremony for advisors from the "New Territories" area
is scheduled for Wednesday.  
</P>
