<HEADLINE> Indonesia, South Africa to Form Economic Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and South Africa have
agreed to set up a joint commission to enhance bilateral trade and
economic ties, Minister/State Secretary Drs Moerdiono said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached by Indonesian President Soeharto and
his South African counterpart Nelson Mandela during their talks at
the Merdeka Palace earlier today.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to form the commission was taken after learning
that the trade volume between the two countries is still low,"
Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to involve the two countries'
private sectors in the economic commission.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Mandela also expressed his country's wish to
host the next non-aligned movement summit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said Indonesia is ready to share its experience of
hosting the summit with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also asked Indonesia to support its bid to hold
the 2004 Olympic games, Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who arrived here Monday for a three-day state visit,
began his visit in Indonesia's island resort of Bali Saturday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Indonesia established diplomatic ties after
South Africa's historic all-race elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries has increased by 309 percent
since 1993. Last year South Africa's exports to Indonesia stood at
167.8 million U.S. dollars, while imports from Indonesia totaled
100.1 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, Mandela will fly to Bangkok for a two-day
visit there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
