<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KEDO Sets South Korean Vessels Test Sail to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Two South Korean vessels set off for
Shinpo Port in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
today in a test run for the transport of machinery and materials
needed to build light-water reactors (LWR).
</P>
<P>
The vessels were sent by the Korean Peninsula Energy
Development Organization (KEDO), a U.S.-led international
consortium which is providing the reactors to the DPRK as part of
a 4.5 billion U.S.-dollar agreement between the U.S. and the DPRK
in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the DPRK agreed to freeze its nuclear program,
which Washington suspected was being used to develop nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
In return, the United States agreed to arrange the provision of
two LWRs generating 1,000 megawatts of power each by around 2003.
</P>
<P>
Since the construction of the LWRs will be done by South Korean
firms, the equipment and materials are being shipped through the
shortest route to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The ships, which left the port of Ulsan in South Korea's North
Kyongsang Province today, will arrive at Yanghwa port in Shinpo,
where the LWRs will be built, on July 17.
</P>
<P>
A DPRK ship will guide the navigation once the vessels enter
its territorial waters, officials from KEDO said.
</P>
<P>
Eleven South Korean crew members, one KEDO staff member and
three South Korean officials related to the LWR project are on
board one barge belonging to the South Korean Express Company.
The vessel is also transporting desks, chairs and other office
equipment for KEDO's office which will be set up in Shinpo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
