<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Dumping Poses Threat in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 17,000 tons of waste
oil dumped, burnt or used as wood preservative in Kenya every
year, posing a serious environmental and economic hazard, a local
press report said today.
</P>
<P>
Although waste oil recycling facilities exist in Kenya, only
500 out of 29,000 tons of used lubricants is recycled annually.
The recycled rate is less than 2 percent, agaisnt nearly
40 percent in Germany, 38 percent in Israel and more than 30
percent in South Africa, said the report.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of waste oil generated by industries in Kenya
is estimated to be burnt in boilers as it is cheaper than fuel
oil.
</P>
<P>
"Some laundry firms buy used oils from garages for use in
their boilers, not realizing that there is chlorine contamination
originating from the use of solvents in degreasing and oil
cleaning," said S. Kantaria, a director of Waste Reclaimers
Kenya, the country's key collector of oil for regeneration.
</P>
<P>
Burning oil contaminated with chlorinated solvents will
produce hydrochloric acid in the emissions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The dumping of oil in Kenya is usually due to ignorance, or a
don't-care attitude, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Oil may end up in the soil in the country because of leaking
tanks or over-turned tankers and often people will throw waste
oil to suppress dust on roads or in sewerage after servicing
vehicles, added the report.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that oils used in Kenya are generally heavier in
sulphur compared with most developed countries, which restrict
sulphur to less than 0.3 percent. The figure in Kenya is more
than one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0114 </DOCNO>
