<HEADLINE> Australia to Suspend Military Aid to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia is to suspend its
military aid to Cambodia following the ouster of First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh by his rival, Second Prime
Minister Hun Sun, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the future of the 1.5 million U.S.-dollar defense
cooperation program, which involves communications training,
maritime maintenance and language training in Cambodia, would
depend upon Cambodia's commitment to peace and democracy.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign minister said Australia's commitment to
mine clearing in Cambodia would continue.
</P>
<P>
He said other major donors would be consulted before Australia
decides on the future of its 24 million U.S.-dollar general aid
program to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"The future of our aid program will take into account whether
the situation on the ground allows for an effective aid program,
the acceptability of the policies of the Cambodian government, and
the views of other major donors and ASEAN countries," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Australian government had made clear
the military overthrow was "completely unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia's recognition of Hun Sen's government was
not an issue, as Australia had a policy of recognizing states, not
governments. 
</P>
