<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Population Grows To 17.89 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia's population rose by
1.04 million, or 6.2 percent, to 17,892,423 during 1991 to 1996,
the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said today.
</P>
<P>
ABS spokesman Stuart Jackson said the population had grown
despite lower levels of immigration in recent years and a drop in
birth rates.
</P>
<P>
Results of the August 1996 census, which were released today,
also show Australia now has more females than males, and the
number of people identifying as aboriginal or Torres Strait
Islanders has jumped 33 percent since the previous census
conducted in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The census showed women outnumbered men in all states except
Western Australia, where the population of two sexes were equal,
and the Northern Territory where men outnumbered women. Nationally
Australia's population is now 50.5 percent female and 49.5 percent
male.
</P>
<P>
The census records a dramatic jump in people identifying as
indigenous following greater publicity on indigenous issues.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 figure of 352,970 aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islanders is 33 percent up from the 1991 figures and 55.1 percent
up from the 1986 figures.
</P>
<P>
According to the census, Australia's population is continuing
to age. The proportion of the population aged over 65 grew from
11.3 percent in 1991 to 12.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The median age of males has increased from 30 years to 33 for
men and from 31 to 34 for women over the 10 years since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Today's data shows there are also more younger people, with
3,852,120 Australians under 15 as compared with 3,764,682 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The number of people born overseas has dropped to 21.8 percent,
from 22.3 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Despite independent MP Pauline Hanson's concerns about the
level of Asian immigration, the statistics show that of
Australians born overseas, 56.7 percent were born in Europe and
the former USSR, 21.9 percent in Asia and 4.9 percent in the
Middle East and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 47.2 percent of Australians over 15 had a yearly
income of less than 11,700 U.S. dollars, with 5.3 percent having
more than 39,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australians renting homes rose from 26.7 percent in 1991 to
28.7 percent last year, while the number of homes owned rose
slightly from 40.4 percent to 40.9 percent, and the number of
homes being purchased dropped from 26.7 percent to 25.5 percent in
1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
