<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Government Takes Measures to Ensure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government led by
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has launched major constitutional
reforms to ensure smooth governance, political stability and
consequently economic development.
</P>
<P>
With the unanimous adoption of the 14th Constitutional
Amendment by the National Assembly on July 1, the 46-year-old
Sharif, who came to power in mid-February, has got another feather
in his cap.
</P>
<P>
The apparent purpose of the 14th Amendment, which bans change
of loyalty by parliamentarians elected on tickets of their
respective parties, is to root out floor-crossing, horse trading
and blackmailing which have become a malaise in the country's
political life, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
"We are introducing structural changes in Pakistan politics,
and as a whole, the nation will feel satisfied with the
performance of the politicians," said the beaming Sharif after all
the members of the National Assembly voted in favor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the majority of governments were thrown out by
forcing the ruling members to change their loyalties," he said.
"We will not do so. We would bury all the ill practices of the
past."
</P>
<P>
The passage of the 14th Amendment is seen as a second landmark
legislative measure by the Sharif government to safeguard its
ruling position.
</P>
<P>
With the passage of the 14th Amendment, Sharif has acquired
full control over his party, the observers said, because the party
members' political fate is now tied to that of the party leaders,
who they can desert and disobey only at the cost of losing their
seats.
</P>
<P>
The Sharif government has also introduced another
constitutional reform removing unrestricted presidential power to
dismiss an elected government.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Pakistan's parliament unanimously adopted the 13th
Amendment to scrap the article in the Constitution empowering the
president to dismiss an elected government and dissolve the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
With the 13th and 14th Amendments in hand plus his party's
majority in parliament, Sharif was likely to avoid premature
departure from power and unnecessary political confrontation, the
observers said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that these constitutional reforms by Sharif's
government in a short span of five months will not only strengthen
the government but also pave the way for carrying out Sharif's
economic reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Post Launches New Performance Pledges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Post launched its new
performance pledges today following a recent customer perception
survey.
</P>
<P>
"Our new Performance Pledges reflect our determination to
provide quality services to our customers," said Robert Footman,
Hong Kong's Postmaster General, at a press briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
The pledges have three "firsts": the results of the first
independent survey of customer views on the services, the Hong
Kong Post's first customer service pledge, and its achievement for
the first time of the pledge to deliver 98 percent of local
letters on the day after collection.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 94 percent of respondents from the
general public, 96 percent of the business sector and 86 percent
from the philately sector were satisfied or extremely satisfied
with the Post's services.
</P>
<P>
The first customer service pledge formalizes Hong Kong Post's
commitment to fulfill needs and exceed expectations, with
professional and caring services which are on time, reliable,
convenient and outstanding value for money.
</P>
<P>
Footman said: "These results demonstrate that 1996 was a good
year for Hong Kong Post. But they also provide the further
impetus to our efforts to improve our services," he said.
</P>
<P>
Plans have been developed to improve in areas identified by
customers in the survey, especially waiting time, customer
friendliness and availability of philatelic products and to reduce
waiting time at the counters, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Post was pressing ahead with new and improved
performance pledges and services, including a freeze on postage
rates until July next year, extend discounts for bulk postings and
a new bulk economy service.
</P>
<P>
Footman assured 11 new pledges for the 1997, including seven
improved pledges, two new pledges and two pledges for new
services.
</P>
<P>
Among them are delivery of all local mail on the day after
collection, serving customers within 10 minutes, delivery of all
outward airmail to the first available flight, delivery of all
inward airmail arriving in Hong Kong before 2:00 p.m. to major
commercial and industrial areas, on the next day, delivery of all
parcels to major commercial and industrial areas within two days
and processing various applications within seven working days.
</P>
</TEXT>
