<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) Chief Executive Joseph Yam has expressed his strong
confidence in the strength of the Hong Kong dollar at a time when
some currencies in Southeastern Asia plunged under heavy
speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar, which is pegged to the US dollar at a
rate of HK$7.780, was not vulnerable to speculators on the
currency market thanks to its underlying strength, today's Hong
Kong Standard quoted Yam as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange rate has been very stable. We're absolutely not
concerned at all," the HKMA Chief Executive was quoted as
saying. Yam's confidence in the local currency came from Hong
Kong's hefty foreign reserves of more than 80 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hong Kong has signed with many Asian countries
repurchase agreements, which ensure the authority has sufficient
liquidity to fight speculators, Yam told another local English
newspaper the South China Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's economy boasts sound fundamentals -- five
to six percent GDP growth per year, a low jobless rate and a
healthy balance sheet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
