<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Tourist Arrivals Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals to Macao in the
first five months dropped 2.4 percent from the same period last
year, the latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that the number of tourists coming to Macao reached
3,200,913, down 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists traveling to Macao plummeted in April
and May, when only 1,198,971 tourists were recorded. The number
increased 2.7 percent in the first quarter of the year, reaching
2,001,942.
</P>
<P>
Comparing with April 1996, tourist arrivals dropped 9.4
percent, and comparing with May last year, the number dropped 10.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attributed the decrease of tourist arrivals
mainly to the result of a negative image to outsiders after an
avalanche of foreign news coverage of Macao's crimes earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the number of passengers from Hong Kong, the
dominant source of tourists for Macao, declined 13.7 percent in
the five months. The number of Japanese tourists dropped 7.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of tourists from Taiwan, China's inland
areas and Britain show a continuous rise.
</P>
<P>
The number of travelers from Taiwan rose 73 percent by May,
from China's inland areas 17 percent and Britain 28.1 percent,
compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Macao tourism officials earlier expected the number of tourists
to reach nine million this year, after it surpassed 8.15 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a big income earner for Macao with a population of
450,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
