<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consular Assistance, Protection Offered to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Embassy in Cambodia
and the Office of the Chinese Foreign Ministry's Commissioner in
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) have done a lot
of work to protect Chinese Hong Kong citizens stranded in
Cambodia, said a spokesman for the Commissioner's Office here
today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that since the military conflict broke out
in the capital Phnom Penh some 10 days ago, they have been working
very closely with the SAR Government in providing consular
assistance and protection to Hong Kong compatriots.
</P>
<P>
He said that when the conflict happened, the Chinese Embassy
immediately called a meeting of representatives from related
companies to give a briefing on the situation in Cambodia, and
arranged a hotline and contacts for Chinese citizens in Cambodian
to get in touch with the Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The Embassy made it clear that all Chinese nationals, including
Hong Kong residents with British National (Overseas) passports,
would be offered consular protection and assistance. At that time
some Chinese Hong Kong citizens were in the warring areas, and the
Embassy assisted them in moving to safe places.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that, in order to provide timely consular
protection, the Embassy issued a public notice twice to invite
Chinese citizens, including Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan
compatriots, to register at the Embassy.
</P>
<P>
So far 79 Hong Kong compatriots have registered at the Embassy,
most of whom have left Cambodia, while the remaining will make
their own decision either to leave or stay, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Embassy has made representations many times with
the Cambodian government, demanding the Cambodian side to adopt
necessary measures to protect the life and property safety of all
Chinese citizens in the country.
</P>
<P>
So far no casualties have been reported among Chinese Hong Kong
citizens, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Office of the Chinese Foreign Ministry's
Commissioner in HKSAR actively cooperated with the Embassy in
Cambodia and kept in close touch with the SAR Government. The
Office made timely reports on Hong Kong people's demand and played
a link-up role.
</P>
<P>
The Office has also opened a hotline to answer Hong Kong
compatriots' inquiries and passed their requirements onto the
Embassy in time, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said at present the Cambodian situation tends to become
stable, and the Embassy has decided that at this moment it does
not consider dispatching planes to evacuate Chinese citizens in
Phnom Penh, but will continue to maintain close contact with them,
so that consular assistance and protection can be offered to them
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Embassy will continue to negotiate with
Cambodian officials and the local police force, and strongly
demand the Cambodian authorities to adopt practical and feasible
measures to protect the life and property safety of all Chinese
citizens in Cambodia, including compatriots from Hong Kong, Macao
and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Office will continue to work closely with
the SAR Government and the Chinese Embassy in Cambodia, so that
the rights and interests of Hong Kong compatriots in Cambodia can
be better protected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
