<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Needs $1bn to Repair Ailing Refineries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria needs 86 billion Naira
(over one billion U.S. dollars) to repair its ailing refineries,
which have led to continuous fuel shortage in this top
oil-producing country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Chief Dan Etete, the petroleum resources minister revealed
this Monday while addressing the Nigerian Guild of Editors in
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that with the money provided, the
rehabilitation of the country's four ailing refineries will take
18 months and will allow them to operate at an average of 85
percent of their installed capacity.
</P>
<P>
The four refineries, two in Port Harcourt, one in Warri and
another in Kaduna, were built seven to 32 years ago. Aging
equipment plus poor maintenance have reduced their production to
half of their capacities.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, none of the four refineries has
undergone thorough maintenance in the last three to four years,
whereas such maintenance should be done in every two years.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the refineries can only produce a total of nine
million litres of fuel everyday, only half of the country's daily
consumption, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the maintenance problem, the minister also called for
the need to hire foreign vessels to lift fuel to Lagos and other
coastal cities, as the existing pipeline systems are aged and
insufficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
