<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Allows No Demonstration Without Written </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma has announced Monday that no more public protests will be
allowed without the written approval of the police.
</P>
<P>
The move follows a demonstration for jobs by 600 ex-combatants
in Oshakati last Tuesday, during which four regional councillors
of the ruling South West Africa People's Organisation (SWAPO)
were held hostage,local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a stern public address made in Windhoek, Nujoma said no
person had the right to "attack physically, molest, hold hostage
or interfere with other citizens" as had happened at Oshakati.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he decreed that in future no citizen would be
allowed to hold public demonstrations without the written
permission by the police.
</P>
<P>
Political parties have the right to organize, politicize,
campaign, recruit members from society, the president said,
adding that this also applied to trade unions and members of
civil society.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that citizens would from now on be able
to do so "only after obtaining permission to hold such
demonstration".
</P>
<P>
The demonstration at Oshakati, that sparked the presidential
decree, followed a two-week protest for jobs by former fighters
in Windhoek, which had government scrambling for solutions.
</P>
<P>
The protest dissolved once Nujoma had personally promised the
fighters jobs in various government ministries and projects,as
well as private companies.
</P>
<P>
About 23,000 former fighters of the People's Liberation Army
of Namibia and the South West Africa Territory Force as well as
the special unit of the former South African police, were
demobilized with independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
