<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Projects in China's Inland Draw Foreign Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Investors are facing increasing
competition in the road building sector, one of the key
infrastructure industries in the Chinese inland areas, according
to a report released today by Salomon Brothers.
</P>
<P>
In its latest research report entitled "China Infrastructure
Sector -- the Road Builders," Salomon Brothers attributed the keen
competition to enhanced access to overseas capital.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), China is
expected to spend 20 billion US dollars on building national
highways. Salomon Brothers forecast that four to five billion US
dollars will be raised in forms of foreign funds, including loans
from the World Bank or the Asian Development Bank, project
financing funds from foreign banks and money pooled from equity
market.
</P>
<P>
Cathy Chang, the regional infrastructure analyst of Salomon
Brothers, said: "The rising number of initial public offerings in
the sector has also reduced the scarcity value of the original
road builders."
</P>
<P>
So far, four highway companies of the Chinese inland areas have
gone public on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, raising a total of
9.273 billion HK dollars (1.190 billion US dollars). Some Hong
Kong-based companies have shifted their focus on infrastructure
investment in inland provinces, mainly toll roads and bridges, and
power plants.
</P>
<P>
Chang expected that the infrastructure boom would continue in
the second half of this year with more new issues in the pipe line
and further fund-raising activities by listed companies.
</P>
<P>
Apart from fund raising on the stock market, debt financing
will become an important channel to pool more foreign funds into
the capital-intensive infrastructure sector in inland
areas. "Raising fund on debt market is generally cheaper than on
equity market," said Chang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
