<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Consumer Price Index Up 2.8 Pct This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's year-on-year
consumer price index (CPI) for the first six months 1997 expanded
2.8 percent to 109.3 against the corresponding period of 1996,
according to the official figures released here today by the
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the CPI which is a measure of inflation during
the January-June period this year was due to increases observed in
the indices of all main groups except for clothing and footwear
which decreased 0.5 percent, the Statistics Department said.
</P>
<P>
The two main groups -- food and gross rent, fuel and power
together -- accounted for 85.8 percent of the overall increases
recorded in the current period under review.
</P>
<P>
The 4.9 percent increase in the index for food was the result
of a 4.2 percent increase for food at home coupled with an
increase of 6.7 percent for food away from home.
</P>
<P>
Eight sub-groups of food at home recorded increases during the
period with higher increases shown by meat (7.1 percent), fish
(6.7 percent), and rice, bread and other cereals (6.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
Other increases recorded were for milk and eggs, other foods,
coffee and tea, sugar, and fruits and vegetables, while the index
for oils and fats decreased 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The CPI for June this year rose 2.2 percent to 109.5 from the
same month last year, and compared with the previous month, it
decreased 0.1 percent, brought on by a 0.2 percent decrease in the
indices of the main group Food.
</P>
<P>
As for beverages and tobacco, furniture and household equipment
and operation, transport and communication and recreation,
entertainment, education and cultural services, the indices in
June remained stable at 105.3, 103.9, 103.8 and 106.2
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
