<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Plan to Quit Commonwealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Nigerian official has
denied that the country had completed arrangements to quit from
the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
Auwadlu Yadudu, the special adviser on legal matters to the
head of state, General Sani Abacha, has described such reports as
"false and untrue".
</P>
<P>
He told the official News Agency of Nigeria last week in
Kaduna State that the country has never contemplated that option
and has no intention of doing so in future.
</P>
<P>
Though the Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership in
November 1995 for executing writer Ken Saro-wiwa and eight other
Ogni activists, Yadudu said it has never threatened to expel
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said Nigeria would remain in the Commonwealth in spite of
all the injustices it faced.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG)
explained Monday that the Commonwealth will decide on whether to
re-admit Nigeria or impose further sanctions on it in November,
when the heads of governments of the Commonwealth Nations will
meet in Scotland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
