<HEADLINE> UN Fund Aids Health Education Program in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Fund for
Population Activities (UNFPA) has granted Sri Lanka 750,000 U.S.
dollars to upgrade health education in primary and secondary
schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA-aided program is expected to help 1.8 million
students between grades 6 and 11 to cope with the changes of
adolescence, education ministry sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Students will be educated on nutrition, AIDS prevention,
population and environment, male responsibilities in family and
gender equality, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that when they grow up these children would be
endowed with the knowledge and attitudes for responsible sexual
behavior and planned families, thereby leading to responsible
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
More that 50,000 teachers will be trained in the program, the
sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
