<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Egyptian Family Income Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptians took home more money
and spent more last year than they did in 1995 when the economic
reform began to pick up its pace, the Arabic Al-Ahram daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A recent study, compiled by the country's Central Agency for
Mobilization and Statistics, showed that the annual average
family income has risen to 7,570 Egyptian pounds (about 2,226
U.S. dollars) in 1996, up by 32.6 percent over 1991.
</P>
<P>
The annual per capita income exceeded 4,500 pounds (1,324
dollars) last year, while each city dweller earned 5,253 pounds
(1,545 dollars) and a country folk got 3,867 pounds (1,137
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, recent social and economic developments in Egypt
have led to the diversification of the income sources of the
Egyptian family and the rising spending in consumption, said the
report of the census that is conducted every five years.
</P>
<P>
The fastest growth in the family expense was made in food,
drinks, education, clothing and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Education took up 4.61 percent of urban's family's total
expenditure in 1996, up from 2.9 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Food remained the largest family spending last year, eating up
56.37 percent of the whole family budget, which was less than the
59.35 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent World Bank rating, Egypt belongs to the
low-income bracket, with an annual per capita income of less than
1,200 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Won't Take New Loans Until Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will not borrow new loans
from abroad until the bulk of its current debt is paid, according
to Finance Minister Anthony Ani.
</P>
<P>
The government reduced the debt to 28.06 billion U.S. dollars
by the end of last year when it redeemed 5.4 billion dollars of
the stock.
</P>
<P>
However, the debt problem remained enormous and must be
confronted head-on, Ani said on Monday, adding that the
government was inclined to aid from multinational donor agencies
in place of loans.
</P>
<P>
With the need to cut down the debt stock, the federal
government has decided to put an embargo on new external loans.
And in the alternative, the government prefers assistance from
such agencies as the World Health Organization (WHO), which the
minister described as very helpful.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks at a workshop in the capital
Abuja on External Aid Negotiation organized by the WHO with his
ministry, the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, WHO Regional Representative Abraham Samba
accused African nations of mismanaging funds from donor
countries, saying that the region defeated the good intention of
most donor entities and still remains largely underdeveloped.
</P>
<P>
The WHO official was, however, faulted by National Planning
Minister Chief Ayo Ogunlade who said most developed countries
sometimes used the less developed ones as avenues to provide
employment for their nationals in the guise of aid.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, the budget for foreign experts and
consultants often takes up more than 60 percent of the aid. After
discounting values for logistic and accommodation, the actual
amount left for the project may be less than 20 percent of the
aid value," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ogunlade, such assistance must fall within the
scope of national rolling plan and budgetary systems for
long-term sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
He called for involvement of local experts in execution of aid
or externally funded projects.
</P>
<P>
It would not only encourage or enhance the sustainability of
such projects after the departure of foreign experts, it would
also facilitate the harmonization of expertise with local needs,
culture, tradition and circumstances, he added.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the workshop are representatives from the six
countries of Gambia, Ghana, Lesotho, Liberia, Nigeria and Zambia.
The forum is expected to last a week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
