<HEADLINE> One Million Shanghai Residents Live in Civilized Communities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Le Junren, a senior resident at
Ganquanyuan Community in Shanghai who was diagnosed with cancer
many years ago, credits his survival from the disease to the clean
and tidy streets, fresh air, and warm friendships in his
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
"If I didn't live in such a nice community, I might already be
dead," Le said.
</P>
<P>
Ganquanyuan is a city-level "Civilized Community," with more
than 8,900 residents and a green coverage of 45 percent, said Gao
Meixia, director of the community office.
</P>
<P>
Tree-lined streets wind through the communities, houses are
surrounded with green plants and the scent of flowers and grass is
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about one million Shanghai people are
living in more than 600 such appealing neighborhoods, which are
characterized by their comfortable environment, stable social
security systems, harmonious neighborhood relations and colorful
recreational activities.
</P>
<P>
The Civilized Community of the No.7 neighborhood committee of
Caoyangwu Village, the first of its kind, was formed in 1989,
designed to provide an attractive and comfortable living
environment for the people working in this modern city.
</P>
<P>
"We begin our 'civilization scheme' by promoting the use of
garbage bags," said Tan Judi, an official with the neighborhood
committee.
</P>
<P>
"At first, people were reluctant to take the trouble to bag
their garbage, but it soon became a habit and they were delighted
to find it was helpful in cleaning the air and cutting down on
flies and mosquitos," Tan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Million Shanghai Residents Live in Civilized Communities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the process of building the Civilized Communities, the
district and sub-district officials also can learn how to settle
the problems in residents' daily life, said Xu Deming, director of
the city's Office for Ethical and Cultural Progress.
</P>
<P>
In Linfen sub-district of Zhabei District, at the meeting point
of the urban and rural areas, it's difficult to find
transportation. The family members of a woman in labor had to
catch a ride from a garbage truck to get her to a nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
Upset by the incident, the director of the sub-district office
organized several units to build nine roads across the community
which lead to various parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
To provide job opportunities for laid-off workers and help
solve difficulties in residents' family life, the Civilized
Communities have developed a number of community services, such as
senior citizens centers, retail vegetable outlets, and
housecleaning services.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that the satisfaction rate of the residents for
their environment soared to over 98 percent, while more than 99
percent of residents supported the building of more such
communities.
</P>
<P>
The contradictions that crop up from the social changes can
easily be dealt with by the common people when they have jobs and
lead pleasant lives, said Huang Ju, secretary of the Shanghai
municipal committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe that's why the society still maintains stability, the
economy develops and reforms are carried out smoothly, in spite of
the fact that an accumulated number of about one million employees
at the State-owned enterprises have been laid off in recent years,
and more than three million transient people flow into the city
each year," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will continue to build the Civilized Communities on a
large scale over the next three years and the number of people
living in them is expected to be three million by the end of
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
