<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Kazak Herdsmen Riding Motorcycles Instead of Horses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- In some pastoral areas of northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, Kazak herdsmen are
putting their trusty steeds out to pasture, replacing them with
motorcycles and other modern means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
For years, the nomadic Kazak people herded their sheep or
cattle and even went shopping on horseback. They believed having
several strong horses tied to a tree in front of their houses was
a sign of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
But in Shitizi Kazak Nationality Township of Hutubi County,
motorcycles and mini-buses are whizzing up and down the village
roads, and people on horseback are becoming a rare sight.
</P>
<P>
The township has more than 800 households of Kazak herdsmen,
who now have bought 210 motorcycles and nearly 300 vehicles of
various types and sizes. Almost every family has a tractor, said
Aguhan, the head of the township.
</P>
<P>
It used to take a Kazak herdsmen a week on horseback to travel
to the county seat from the mountains where they live, a journey
of more than 100 km. As a result, they never went to town in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
"Now herdsmen come here by motorcycles instead of horses, as
they used to. The modern transportation means save them time and
protect the environment," Aguhan said, pointing to the motorcycles
parked in front of the township building.
</P>
<P>
The county government spent more than a million yuan in 1994 to
build a highway leading to the township. Some herdsmen have become
well-to-do enough to buy mini-buses to carry passengers to town, a
trip of several hours.
</P>
<P>
In villager Hasm's home, visitors were impressed by two Honda
motorcycles, a large tractor, a four-wheeled tractor, and a fodder
grinder. His family earned nearly 60,000 yuan last year, raising
60 sheep, 17 heads of cattle, growing more than six ha of wheat
and maize.
</P>
<P>
"Convenient transportation makes it possible to get new
knowledge quickly, and I have learned to apply advanced technology
to planting and breeding to raise my income," Hasm said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Tests Electrical Interference On GPS Users </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Defense Force
(ADF) is testing this week how electrical interference affects the
Global Positioning System (GPS) by transmitting electrical jamming
signals from the ground and air.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Defense Department spokesman Richard Hogan said the
trials could affect the accuracy of GPS equipment used within a
450 km radius of Woomera airfield, in South Australia's mid-north,
between today and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He warned users of the system, a global satellite navigation
system, not to rely on it this week because trials taking place at
the Woomera airfield could interfere with the accuracy of the
service.
</P>
<P>
The GPS is used by the ADF, aircraft, bushwalkers and trucking
companies, with users receiving signals from satellites to
pinpoint their position within a couple of meters accuracy.
</P>
<P>
The ADF and Airservices Australia are testing how electrical
interference affects the GPS users in the test area.
</P>
<P>
The signals will be transmitted in 10-minute bursts to avoid
seriously disrupting the GPS during the trials.
</P>
<P>
The GPS satellite navigation system being tested receives
signals from 24 satellites in six orbital plains 24 km above the
earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
