<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Fall to Lowest Level Since June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market today
fell to its lowest level since early June, hampered by skepticism
over the timing of a possible interest rate cut, a scarcity of
investors and a weak Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading, the benchmark all ordinaries index was
down 35.4 points to 2637.6, its lowest level since June 11 when
the index closed at 2613.7.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a paltry 295.14 million shares traded
worth 751.06 million Australian dollars (552 million U.S.
dollars), with falls outnumbering rises 735 to 371.
</P>
<P>
"The market is taking a breather after going a little bit too
hard on expectations of an interest rate cut," broker Hamish Dee
said.
</P>
<P>
"People are a little bit skeptical of when it's actually going
to happen, in fact if it will happen," Dee added.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 13.3 points down to 1420.8,
while the all industrials plunged 62.7 points to 4205.0.
</P>
<P>
The bank sector was also savaged, tumbling almost two percent
or 92.1 points to 4898.5.
</P>
<P>
NAB Bank dived 43.8 cents, Westpac Bank dropped 26 cents, ANZ
fell 17 cents and the Commonwealth Bank eased 11 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 13.1 points to 1276.7, while in Sydney,
gold bullion was trading at 319.10 U.S. dollars per fine ounce,
down from Monday's close of 321.75.  
</P>
</TEXT>
