<HEADLINE> Rate Sentiment Keeps Australian Dollar Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Concerns about the Reserve Bank
of Australia's (RBA) next move on official interest rates kept the
Australian dollar lower against its U.S. counterpart today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended trading at 73.57 U.S. cents, down
from 73.83 Monday, but off an 18-month low of 73.45 U.S. cents hit
during this morning's trade.
</P>
<P>
The local currency hit a high today of 73.71 after trading
between 73.60 and 73.90 offshore overnight.
</P>
<P>
Chase Manhattan's senior dealer Andrew McGill said that
offshore traders tonight could continue to test the currency's
downside.
</P>
<P>
Many market participants think the RBA could cut the 5.5
percent cash rate following the release of quarterly inflation
data on July 23 and wages data due July 24.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank's July currency report said today that there was
little scope for a meaningful recovery in the Australian currency
while the economy remained soft and RBA easing prospects remained
high.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 84.05 from 83.89 against the
Japanese yen and was at 1.3168 from 1.3138 against the German
mark. 
</P>
