<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks Plunge Over Uncertainty Around Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Stocks at the Philippine Stock
Exchange plunged today due to uncertainty about where the peso is
settling down after it was allowed to float freely.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Philippine Stock Exchange composite index, a
basket of 30 companies, fell 54.87 points, or two percent to close
at 2655.86 points.
</P>
<P>
It surged by 9.59 points on Monday, the first day of trading
after the Central Bank announced the de facto devaluation of the
peso. Last Friday, the index registered a 190-point increase, the
biggest one-day growth in four and a half years.
</P>
<P>
At today's session, the broader all-share index dropped by 17.4
points to 853.19 points. All sectors declined, led by the mining
sector which was followed by the commercial-industrial, the banks
and financial services sector, the property and oil sectors.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5.56 billion shares worth 64 million U.S. dollars
was traded. Declines outnumbered advances 120 to 16 with 41
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said most dealers adopted a wait-and-see
attitude due to the volatility on the country's foreign exchange
market. At one point on Monday, the peso devalued to 29.75 pesos
against one dollar, the lowest in two years, before closing at
28.77 pesos to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Bank's statement that it would intervene
in the market again at a proper time also fed speculation and kept
some foreign investors outside the local bourse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
