<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erenhot's Water Supply to Be Short No More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Erenhot, a trading port on the
China-Mongolia border, has changed its former image as a city
without water.
</P>
<P>
The harsh climate and other natural conditions left the city
suffering from frequent severe water shortages. Water from deep
wells drilled by local people was undrinkable because of its high
flourine content.
</P>
<P>
During the early 1980s, visitors from neighboring Mongolia used
beer and mineral water to wash up, said a director from the city's
water company.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, aided by the central and regional authorities, Erenhot
invested about 40 million yuan to build two pipes from a water
source discovered 60 kilometers outside the city, the director
said.
</P>
<P>
The city's daily water output now amounts to 15,000 tons, which
is enough for a city with a population of 100,000. And Erenhot,
with less than 60,000 residents, plans to send its surplus water
to Dzamin Uud, a small town in Mongolia 4.5 km from Erenhot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0164 </DOCNO>
