<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Improves in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The overall flood situation improved
further today due to stoppage of heavy downpour in most parts of
Bangladesh and resultant fall in the flow of most rivers in the
Meghna and southeastern hill basins.
</P>
<P>
According to the Flood Information Center, the overall flood
situation in southern Chittagong, Cox's Bazar, Bandarban and
Khagrachhari districts is expected to improve further today while
the flood situation in some northern districts will start
improving.
</P>
<P>
However, the center forecast that more areas of northwestern
Kurigram and Sirajganj districts may be inundated.
</P>
<P>
A bulletin of the center said the Ganges was rising fast and
might flow above the danger level at Goalundo within next 24
hours. As a result, low-lying areas of some nearby districts may
be inundated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the road-link between Chittagong and Cox's Bazar
which remained snapped for five days was restored Monday as water
receded from the highway. But the Dhaka-Sylhet road communication
remains suspended due to the collapse of a bridge over the river
Khowai.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said a huge amount of food, clothes, rice and
cash has been sanctioned among the flood affected people from the
Prime Minister's Relief Fund.
</P>
<P>
A government handout said the Ministry of Disaster Management
and Relief has sanctioned 655,000 taka (about 15,000 U.S.
dollars), 161 tons of rice, 1,500 cans of biscuit, flattened rice
and fried rice for distribution in the affected districts.
</P>
<P>
As many as 20 tons of rice have been reserved for each district
to meet emergencies caused by flood and other natural hazards, the
handout said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
