<HEADLINE> Philippine President Supports Misuari's Peace Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today ordered
the military and police in the southern Philippines to support a
local governor's mission to restart the stalled peace talks
between the government and the Muslim rebels.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' order was conveyed personally by Presidential Management
Staff head Alexander Aguirre to regional police director Frank
Clida and Maj. Gen. Raul Urgello, commander-general of the Army's
6th Infantry Division.
</P>
<P>
Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao, met with Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) vice
chairman Hadji Murad last week in renewed efforts to resume the
peace talks between the MILF and the government.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said Misuari and Murad agreed on the need to normalize
the situation in Mindanao and the MILF's return to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the two sides should cease fire, keep
open the roads and highways in their areas of conflicting and
cooperate in the anti-kidnapping campaigns in Mindanao, Aguirre
said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the government and the MILF are trying to re-open
their sixth round of low-level talks following the military's
recent offensives in which dozens of MILF rebels were killed.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, also chief of the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF), offered himself as a peace mediator between the government
and the MILF. But it was reported that the MILF has refused
Misuari's offer.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member breakaway faction of the mainstream
MNLF which signed a peace agreement with the government last year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
