<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Able to Sustain Policies despite Speculative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has been able to
sustain its present economic and monetary policies despite
speculative attacks on its currency, acting prime minister Anwar
Ibrahim said today.
</P>
<P>
Speculative attacks were more aggressive in some countries,
forcing them to respond in a manner not necessarily according to
the direction they had planned for, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
But "in our case, we have been fortunate to have been able to
sustain this but will have to be realistic to balance between a
reasonable exchange rate", Anwar, who is also Finance Minister,
told newsmen after officiating the "International Islamic Capital
Market" conference here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's local currency ringgit opened at 2.5650/80 against
the US dollar today from 2.5340/60 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit slipped to a low of 2.5700 during New York trading,
a level last seen about three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Anwar turned down the overheating factor as one of the reasons
for the speculative pressure on the local currency, saying it was
the bloating estimates by certain quarters over the country's mega
projects that should be blamed.
</P>
<P>
These "irresponsible estimates" had portrayed different views
of the country's economic growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to see the development in the next few weeks...we have
seen speculators achieving major successes in some countries...we
have our policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the end, it is the country's fundamentals that
determined the value and the strength of the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Based on the existing fundamentals, the present temporary "over
correction" of the ringgit would eventually come to an end, he
said, adding that "I believe the ringgit is already returning to
its fundamentals."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
