<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The British Department for International Development
(DFID) will allot a grant totalling 2 million British pounds
(about 3.4 million U.S. dollars) for two projects in Jordan,
according to a British Embassy statement obtained here today.
</P>
<P>
The first project, "capacity building of the ministry of
social development," aims to develop the ministry's role as a
policy maker and coordinator of social sector activities,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Training workshops will be designed to meet the needs of
ministry staff at central and governorate levels, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The second project is the "Capacity Building of Queen Zein
Al-Sharaf Complex for Development."
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian Former Prime Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti
is most likely to be elected board chairman of the Jordan-Kuwait
Bank during the bank`s general assembly meeting to be held in this
week, semi-official Jordan Times Monday quoted banking sources in
Amman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti has expressed his willingness to assume the post,
although he has also received a number of post offers from other
Jordanian financial institutions and banks, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti became prime minister in 1996 and resigned in March
1997.
</P>
<P>
When he was the prime minister, Kabariti pushed through a
series of economic reforms that all his predecessors had hesitated
to adopt. Kabariti also served in several previous cabinets as
foreign minister, minister of labor and minister of tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan-Kuwait Bank's capital is now 20 million Jordanian
dinars (about 28 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Kuwaiti ties is picking up as regular direct
commercial flights between the two countries' capitals were
resumed in this month and the volume of bilateral trade enjoyed
an increase in the past months.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The total volume of investment in Jordan in 1996
increased by 30 percent than that of 1995 because the investment
promotion law came into force at the beginning of 1996, according
to the Jordan Investment Promotion (JIP).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, total investment in Jordan's different sectors
amounted to 354 million Jordanian dinars (about 495 million
U.S. dollars), with tourism, industrial maritime transport,
agriculture and hospital sectors generating the largest shares,
semi-official Jordan Times Sunday quoted JIP Director General Reem
Badran as saying.
</P>
<P>
This was a 30 percent increase over that of 1995, the director
general said.
</P>
<P>
Investors so far have requested to carry out 15 projects worth
105 million dinars (about 148 million dollars), Badran said.
</P>
<P>
JIP has approved 13 projects by local and foreign investors
worth 95 million dinars (about 134 million dollars) in industry
and tourism, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian ministry of industry and trade is planning to
create a committee grouping representatives from various
ministries and departments to issue licenses for the investors,
the director general said.
</P>
<P>
He said that now no minimum volume of capital for local and
foreign investors will be required to start a project.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Being part and parcel of Egypt's economic reform
program, the wheel of privatization keeps rolling as 26
state-owned companies are to be put up for sale during the first
half of next year, Egypt's MENA news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ten companies, dealing with steel, pipes, textiles, rice and
cotton, will be offered for subscription during the first quarter
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The other 16 companies, dealing with copper, transport, paper
and other businesses will be put up for sale to a principal
investor via the stock exchange from April to June of
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
