<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Unveils Railways 2000 Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel has started a
long-awaited Railways 2000 program to remarkably improve its
railway services, reported the Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Amos Uzani, director-general of Israel Railways, announced
Monday that the Railways 2000 program includes plans for
widespread improvements and new services.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the Tel Aviv-Netanya service along the
Mediterranean coast will be extended to Binyaminna.
</P>
<P>
The single journey time of the four daily non-stop trains
between Haifa and Tel Aviv will be shortened from one hour to 50
minutes, thanks to signalling improvements and the doubling of the
track.
</P>
<P>
The number of daily services on the Tel Aviv-Netanya route
will be increased from 59 to 67.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a greater number of trains operating to
Ashdod, a port city in south Israel, with the completion of
signalling work in Mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
He said that current budgetary restrictions prevent the
upgrading of the existing service for years, but stopping short of
disclosing the cost of the program.
</P>
<P>
Uzani also announced the long-term intention to operate
double-decker trains, with the introduction of the first
electrified lines to Kfar Sava and Rishon Lezion, two towns not
far from Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Israel Railways expects a record 6.3 million passengers this
year, but maintains that with a steady increase of its
annual budget over the next five years, that total could reach
44 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
