<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Jordan's Poverty Rate Down to 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 15 (Xinhua) - The current number of Jordanian
families living under the line of absolute poverty is estimated at
9 percent, a drop of 5.5 percentage points compared with that of
1994, according to a senior Jordanian official.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, families living near the poverty line has been
estimated at 150,000 which accounts for almost 21 percent of the
total population of 4.139 million, Minister of Social Development
Mohammed Kheir Mamser said at a seminar held in the University of
Jordan Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mamser noted that families that earn less than 102 Jordanian
dinars about 144 U.S. dollars per month are considered as living
under the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's seminar, Mamser said that the improvement of
poverty situation could be attributed to the government's
continuous efforts to curb poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He also said some new government projects would be carried out
in further efforts to get rid of poverty. But the minister did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Poverty remains a serious problem for the kingdom that defies
a simple or quick solution, according to a Jordanian government
release in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the number of people living under the poverty line
decreased to 18 percent from 30 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's economy suffered considerably in the 1991 Gulf War to
end the Iraqi occupation of Kuwait, during which Jordan was
sympathetic to the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro-Mediterranent Economic Conference Ends in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Medpartennariat Jordan `97 (the
Euro-Mediterranean economic conference) ended here late Monday
night with mixed reactions from its organizers and local
participants and media.
</P>
<P>
While local participants and media said that they could not see
concrete results from the conference, in which representatives
from 350 European, 22 Israeli and 150 Jordanian companies
participated, the organizers noted that it yielded positive
results.
</P>
<P>
Farouq Hadidi, Director General of Jordan Export Development
Commercial Centers Corporation (JEDCCC) which organized the
conference, told reporters that the conference provided all
participants with export and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Most of the meetings held between Jordanian and foreign
companies were successful and some deals were initialed between
them for future trading and industrial projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hadidi said that these future deals will place Jordan as a gate
to neighboring countries and facilitate the transfer of
technology in industrial investment field.
</P>
<P>
He rejected reports that most of the European companies were
looking at Jordan as a market for their products, saying that the
European companies were seeking partners who can make products
with their trademarks under licence.
</P>
<P>
Some participants from foreign companies noted that the
conference did result in several preliminary agreements for
future joint ventures and export projects.
</P>
<P>
However, local businessmen said that they had hoped to see more
concrete results from the conference, such as the establishment of
joint venture projects.
</P>
<P>
"You can not do business at the Medpartenariat," said Anwar
Obeidat, secretary of the Jordan-Europe Business Association.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the results of the conference
were not fully optimistic as expected.
</P>
<P>
"The Medpartenariat Jordan `97 ended on a subdued note Monday,
with local participants speaking reservedly on the event`s
success," Jordan Times reported.
</P>
<P>
"We were looking for underlicensing manufacturing partners,
but most companies were coming here to sell," it quoted a
Jordanian businessman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, which opened Saturday, was aimed at
enhancing economic cooperation among countries of the
Mediterranean region and the European Union (EU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
