<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Wants Orderly Foreign Exchange Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Central Bank governor Gabriel
Singson said today that the Philippine monetary authorities would
continue making efforts to support an orderly foreign exchange
market.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue with a firm monetary policy stance to support
our decision last Friday, July 11 to allow the peso to float more
flexibly," he said.
</P>
<P>
In line with this approach, he said, the Central Bank is
maintaining its overnight and 5-day borrowing rates at the current
32 and 25 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank offered a new two-week instrument, also
at 25 percent while raising its one-month borrowing rate to 25
percent from 12.37 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are sending strong monetary signals to let the market
realize that while the peso will be allowed to float more
flexibly, we also want to see orderly market conditions. We expect
the foreign exchange market to calm down and stabilize in the next
couple of days," he said.
</P>
<P>
Before announcing the free floating of the peso, the Central
Bank intervened in the foreign exchange market by heavily selling
U.S. dollars to stabilize the peso, which was under speculative
attacks due to the depreciation of the Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
However, the costly but futile intervention made the country's
U.S. dollar reserve shrink to 10 billion from 12 billion in just
10 days. To preserve the foreign exchange reserve and the economic
growth rate, the bank abruptly changed its tune and announced the
de facto devaluation of the peso last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank said that it would intervene again if the
situation in the foreign exchange market runs out of control.
</P>
<P>
When the peso devalued to a four-year low of 29.75 pesos
against the dollar on Monday, the bank sold half a million dollars
to guide the market. The exchange rate then closed at 28.77 pesos
against one U.S. dollar, much better than expected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forum Celebrating 50th Anniversary of establishment of Inner-Mongolia Autonomous Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A forum celebrating the 50th
anniversary of the establishment of the Inner-Mongolia Autonomous
Region was held at the Great Hall of the People here today.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, said at the forum that the region's economy has
developed rapidly since China's reform and opening up drive was
launched in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The region's gross national product has increased by 49 times
over that reported in 1947, and its financial income has increased
by 103,000 times.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the region's experience has proved that the
existence and development of the region can be credited to the
leadership of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that to uphold the autonomous region system,
China must focus on economic development, and at the same time
safeguard and strengthen the unity of each ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
Buhe pointed out there are nearly 170,000 cadres of minority
ethnic groups in the region, making up one-fourth of the total
number of cadres there, and he praised the achievements made by
the regional government in training the cadres of the various
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhaoguo, vice chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, said at the
forum that the region's various ethnic groups have maintained a
good relationship since its establishment.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to uphold and perfect the autonomous region
system, fully carry out the Law on Regional Autonomy For China's
Minority Nationalities, and work out and improve related laws,
regulations and supervisory systems, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
