<HEADLINE> U.S. to Aid Zimbabwe's Low-Income Housing Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's low-income housing
program will receive a further boost of 200 million Zimbabwe
dollars (about 18 million U.S. dollars) this fiscal year, a U.S.
official said.
</P>
<P>
The official from the U.S. Agency for International
Development (USAID) said that the aid will help about 5,000
housing units.
</P>
<P>
The official said here yesterday that the money would also
come with a technical assistance package worth 3.68 million U.S.
dollars for the computerization of business systems of the
registry of deeds and companies, capacity building of local
authorities, the training of small-scale contractors, assistance
to the surveyor-general's office.
</P>
<P>
The mobilization of private sector resources to address the
country's low-income shelter needs and secondary mortgage market
and municipal finance studies are also included in the program,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the computerization of the deeds and companies
registry would result in deeds searches, transfers and
registration being done quickly, making the registry here one of
the most modern in Africa. 
</P>
