<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reforms Elementary Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Many primary and middle schools in
China have initiated educational reforms to solve the problems
caused by putting undue emphasis on the proportion of students
admitted to higher-level schools.
</P>
<P>
Since the resumption of the national entrance examination in
1987, the advantages enjoyed by university graduates in many
aspects have led parents, students and even school authorities to
view high test scores as the only aim of education.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the number of students who are good at
test-taking but do not excel in other areas has aroused the
concern of the education community. Backed by education departments,
some schools have carried out reforms in the examination system to
improve students' overall competence.
</P>
<P>
Yantai, in east Shandong Province, was the first city in China
to carry out such reforms in 1984. The local government abolished the
unified graduation exam for primary school students so that they
can enter the middle school nearest to their homes without taking any
exams.
</P>
<P>
In middle schools, students with different academic abilities
receive classroom instruction at their own level, and those who
choose not to attend high school are sent to vocational high
schools at grade four.
</P>
<P>
Qiqihar, in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, introduced
a new examination system in its primary schools in 1993. The
tests, which formerly took place only at the end of a term, are
now offered throughout the whole course of a term.
</P>
<P>
The testing takes many forms, including questionnaires,
contests and homework, which are offered at random, thus
alleviating test-taking anxiety that some students experience.
</P>
<P>
The reform in exams is bound to cause reform in how to assess
the competence of each student. Many cities have substituted a
grading system for the former 100-point system. The everyday
performance of a student will be noted on a report card and teachers
write comments about the students' performance once a month.
</P>
<P>
Some schools are also going all out to create a comfortable
study environment for children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Imports Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has imported about 120,000
tons of white maize from Zimbabwe to increase its grain stocks,
according to local press today.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the maize consignment was announced by Chance
Kabaghe, director of the Food Reserve Agency (FRA), on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The maize has been imported to address the country's
anticipated grain shortage this year, according to the FRA.
</P>
<P>
The imported maize will be sold to grain traders and millers
wishing to purchase white maize, Kabaghe said.
</P>
<P>
Kabaghe also disclosed that there is urgent need for Zambia to
restock its strategic maize reserves as the national reserve
stocks only have 15,000 tons of white maize instead of the
required 270,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Zambian farmers have reduced their maize planting areas
because of the unstable prices which made them little profits in
1996 when there was a good harvest.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the weather conditions have not been in favor of
grain growing in some parts of the country this year. Hence the
anticipation of grain shortage, said the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
