<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Civilians Killed in Bombardment in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Two civilians have been killed
and another one wounded when artillery shells fired by a
Israeli-backed militia crashed into the village of Berti, some
50 kilometers south of Beirut, the Daily Star reported this
morning.
</P>
<P>
The only English daily in Lebanon noted that Monday night's
bombardment by the South Lebanon Army (SLA), bringing to three the
number of civilians killed in the south since the weekend,
signalled an expansion of war to areas previously unaffected by
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The bombing came in response to a Hezbollah attack on a SLA
patrol in the north sector of the so-called "security zone" in
south Lebanon established by Israel in 1985, which left two
militiamen wounded.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Beirut, the pro-Iranian Hezbollah,
or Party of God, claimed its fighters attacked the patrol with
"automatic weapons and rocket-propelled grenades", destroying an
SLA armored vehicle and "killing and wounding all the members
of its crew."
</P>
<P>
The bombardment began immediately after the attack, with more
than a hundred 155mm shells fired from Zafata and Majidieh in
the Israeli-occupied buffer zone hitting the area, according to
police sources.
</P>
<P>
Laiqa Marmar, 70, a Palestinian and her son Ahmed, 30, were
both killed while her 12-year-old daughter Ahlam was wounded
in the bombardment of Berti, 10 kilometers east of the south
Lebanese port city of Sidon, police sources in the city said.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the South radio, run by the Israeli client
militia, claimed that the shelling was prompted by the wounding
of the two militiamen.
</P>
<P>
During the fatal shelling, two Israeli warplanes fired two
air-to-surface missiles at Kfar Melki in Iglim Al-Toffah, a
ridge often used by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas as a springboard
to launch attacks on the border strip. No casualties were caused
in the air raid, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment of Berti, a mixed Muslim and Christian
village located outside the normal areas of retaliation by
Israel and the SLA, apparently fulfilled the threats made last
month by Antoine Lahd, commander of the SLA, who warned that
villages east of Sidon would be targeted by his artillery if his
militiamen remained under the attack by guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move Monday, the south Lebanon-based
U.N. peacekeeping forces publicly condemned for the first time the
recent Israeli shelling of civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
After talks with the Lebanese foreign minister, Major General
Stanislaw Wozniak, the commander of the 45,000-strong U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), said "We cannot in fact do much in
these cases but we have addressed a strongly-worded protest to
the Israelis over intensifying their shelling which hit
residential areas."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
