<HEADLINE> China Tries to Expand Chain Store Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China will build a number of
large-scale chain stores each exceeding 10 billion yuan (1.2
billion US dollars) in annual sales in the coming five to ten
years, according to a plan released recently by the Ministry of
Internal Trade.
</P>
<P>
The plan also says that this year, three chain stores each
exceeding one billion yuan (120.4 million US dollars) in annual
sales, and 50 that each top 100 million yuan in annual sales will
be built.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Bangzhu, minister of Internal Trade, the
fast-emerging chain store business in China has become a new
growth area in the commodity distribution sector after achieving
remarkable economic returns and obtaining public approval in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
"The focus on further development of the business will be on
expanding the business scale and improving the management," the
minister told a meeting on chain store business which was held
recently in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China had over 700 chain store businesses
with a total of over 10,000 stores operating across the country.
</P>
<P>
The sales of the chain stores accounted for 1.2 percent of the
total commodity retail sales nationally, and in 35 large
cities such as Beijing and Shanghai, the proportion reached 4.1
percent and 6.9 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
They are operating mainly in the form of supermarkets,
warehouse stores, convenience stores, department stores,
speciality shops and snack shops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
