<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Airways' Net Profit in Huge Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Airways' net profit dropped
by 39.5 percent to 852 million Shillings (15.7 million U.S.
Dollars) last year, according to the airline's audited accounts
for the year ending on March 31.
</P>
<P>
The figure stood at 1.4 billion Shillings (25.9 million
Dollars) in the previous year, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, the airline's total income rose by 6.6 percent from
10 billion Shillings (185.2 million Dollars) in 1995 to 10.7
billion Shillings (198.1 million Dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The airline made a loss of 322 million Shillings (5.96 million
Dollars) in foreign exchange in 1996 compared to a gain of 400
million Shillings (7,4 million Dollars )in the previous year,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total costs increased by 10.1 percent because
of higher fuel and labor costs. Higher worldwide oil prices
increased the price of aviation fuel, resulting in a 22 percent
rise in the company's fuel bill.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, total labor costs also rose by 27 percent, adding an
extra 324 million Shillings (six million Dollars) to overheads.
</P>
<P>
The largest increase was pilots' costs where pay and related
benefits shot up over 200 percents, accounting for 234 million
Shillings (4.3 million Dollars) of the total payroll costs.
</P>
<P>
The number of passengers carried jumped to 788,272, a rise of
eight percent compared to the previous year. Improvements were
recorded in both the domestic and international markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
