<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov on Monday
told his visiting British counterpart Robin Cook that regional
conflicts should be addressed in the Russia-NATO ministerial
meeting scheduled for September in New York.
</P>
<P>
When talking about the agenda of the meeting, Primakov
suggested that the issue of Bosnia be discussed and that an armed
force made of both Russian and NATO troops be set up to deal with
possible regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- A five-day joint military exercise by several North
Atlantic Treaty Organization members and partners of the Western
military alliance began in Slovakia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Air forces of the United States, Italy, Turkey, France,
Austria, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Romania, Slovakia and other
countries joined the military exercise, aiming at improving
coordination in the air and getting experience of evacuating
civilians during war time.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said on Monday
that a meeting of foreign ministers from relevant countries will
be held at the end of this month to discuss new initiatives to
help restore stability in Albania after the general elections on
June 29 put a new cabinet to place.
</P>
<P>
Meeting envoys of 14 European Union members to Italy, Dini said
that new international assistance should be ensured in the
economic reconstruction of the Balkan country as the date for the
Italy-led multinational forces to withdraw approaches.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- President of the Republic of Serbia Slobodan
Milosevic was nominated by the Federal Assembly (parliament) of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Monday as the sole candidate
for the Yugoslav presidency.
</P>
<P>
Both houses of the Yugoslav federal parliament unanimously
adopted a motion which chose Milosevic as the presidential
candidate of the nation, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. State Department on Monday said that
there is no evidence that Americans were behind the bombing of two
hotels in Cuba's capital of Havana this weekend.
</P>
<P>
"There's no evidence whatsoever that Americans were behind it,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cuba has charged that the U.S. government is behind the
bombing, which injured two Cubans on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States announced Monday that it will
provide 27 million U.S. dollars more in food aid for the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea as a response to the latest
appeal from the U.N. World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
"In response to the World Food Program's announcement July 9 of
an expanded appeal for humanitarian food aid for children in North
Korea, the United States government has decided to extend 100,000
metric tons of grain valued at approximately 27 million dollars,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters. 
</P>
