<HEADLINE> France Did Not Support Mobutu: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HRARARE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- French Ambassador to Zimbabwe
Jacques Migozzi denied Monday recent claims by the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) leadership that France had armed and
supported ousted president Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
Migozzi told the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana that France did
not have much to benefit or to protect by supporting Mubutu in
the wake of the offensive by Laurent Kabila's forces.
</P>
<P>
"We did not have many business interests in former Zaire.
besides, I have not noticed any specific accusations against
France," he said.
</P>
<P>
Migozzi was reluctant to discuss the issue in detail, opting
to talk about the disappearance of Rwandan refugees in the DRC
who were being investigated by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The DRC is among Africa's mineral rich countries and has large
oil, diamond, gold and copper deposits. Since Kabila took power
in May, it has been in the centre of a mineral scramble from big
multi-national mining companies.
</P>
<P>
France had been accused of providing military aid to the
fallen Mubutu regime which was toppled by then rebel leader
Kabila last May after 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
President Kabila's Finance Minister Mawapagna Mwana Nanga said
recently the French contingent in Brazzaville supplied weapons to
the former presidential guard. 
</P>
