<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fishing Ban Announced at Offshore Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China will impose a fishing ban in
the Yellow Sea and East China Sea in July and August, in a bid
to protect certain species of fish, the Ministry of Agriculture
(MA) announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry's decision, no trawl boats will be
permitted to fish in July and August in the area that extends from
27 degrees to 35 degrees north latitude.
</P>
<P>
Over the next two months, boats can fish only in areas 30
nautical miles east of offshore and a system to check the number
of young fish will be strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
This is the third consecutive year that China has declared a
two-month no-fishing season.
</P>
<P>
Facts have proved that such a ban is the most effective way
to protect the country's offshore fishing resources, said a
ministry official.
</P>
<P>
After first no-fishing season, the output of hairtail fish grew
by 14 percent to a record 740,000 tons in 1995. The weight
of each hairtail increased from 80-100 grams to 125 grams. The
output of little yellow croaker, silvery pomfret, prawn and crabs
had also increased to various extents, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local governments can make use of the off-season to
readjust their operational structure and hold training courses
for fishermen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
