<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Oil Products to Rise in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Prices of imported crude and
petroleum products and power rates are likely to rise slightly in
the Philippines due to the devaluation of the peso, the Philippine
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the government institutions said the increases
would be "minimal" because of the prevailing low prices on the
world market, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a senior official of the Energy and Regulatory Board
as saying that for every one-peso depreciation, there might be a
corresponding increase of about 0.1 to 0.2 pesos in the average
price of petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The peso devalued from 26.40 pesos to 28.77 pesos against the
U.S. dollar on Monday, the first day of trading after the Central
Bank announced the free floating of the Philippine currency last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The fall of the peso's value was generally viewed as a positive
move and welcomed by the business sector. However, it also raised
worries over the increase in prices of basis commodities and
higher inflation in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
