<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 07:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Troops on Full Alert for Fear of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli troops were on full
alert along the northern border and in the Israel-occupied
security zone in south Lebanon Monday night for fear of
retaliation after Israeli army killed two Lebanese civilians,
reported the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Lebanese resistance guerrilla organization,
Hezbollah, had earlier warned of Katyusha rocket retaliation on
the Galilee districts in northern Israel, if Israel persisted in
consistent breaches of the Operation Grapes of Wrath
understandings.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached between Israel and Hezbollah with
the help of the U.S. and France in April last year, Israel would
not attack civilian targets while the guerrillas promised not to
fire Katyusha rockets on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The warnings by Hezbollah spiritual leader Sheikh Mohammed
Hussein Fadlallah and other leading officials were made after a
70-year-old Lebanese villager was killed by an Israeli tank
fire, but before the latest incident, in which a woman and her
son were reported to have been killed and a girl wounded as a
result of Israeli heavy fire.
</P>
<P>
The wounded girl and the bodies of those killed were brought
to hospital in Sidon. They were reportedly hit during heavy
Israeli shelling of Berti village, east of the southern Lebanese
port city.
</P>
<P>
Maj.-Gen. Amiram Levine, head of the Israeli army Northern
Command, Monday night warned Hezbollah not to launch Katyusha
rocket attacks. He declared that the Israeli army would respond
severely.
</P>
<P>
A heated debate has been going on across political spectrum
in Israel on whether Israel should withdraw from south Lebanon
unilaterally. Some parents of the soldiers in south Lebanon have
formed a group lobbying for an end of the costly, decade-old war
in the Lebanese territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
