<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Urges to Set up Council on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's opposition parties, in
response to President Daniel arap Moi's signals on reforms, has
urged to set up a broad-based national consultative council to
discuss the timetable for minimum constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The council should be established immediately, said three
senior members from the Inter-Parties Committee which include the
Democracy Party and the FORD-Kenya, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mukhisa Kituyi from the FORD-Kenya said the council composed
of representatives from political parties, organized civil
society and religious groups would be expected to agree on the
modalities of holding peaceful elections.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is seen as a shift from the hard line stand
earlier taken by the opposition over the issue. It came after the
most violent clashes between the government and the opposition
rallies claimed 14 lives around the country on July 7.
</P>
<P>
Moi announced on Friday that he would call top-level meetings
of his ruling Kenyan African National Union (KANU) to deliberate
on constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders said on Saturday that they doubted Moi's
sincerity, arguing that it was a way of buying time.
</P>
<P>
In response, KANU National Chairman Wilson Ndolo Ayah said on
Monday the party is willing to engage in dialogue on
constitutional reforms with registered political parties with a
concrete agenda.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to talk with anybody who has a clear vision of
the constitutional changes that the country needs, but we will
not listen to groups of people who specialize only in making
noise and hurling insults at others," he said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have been putting pressures on
President Daniel arap Moi to conduct constitutional reforms
before the forthcoming general elections, while Moi insists he
only do that after the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
Now the opposition leaders urged to change the clause,
demanding the future president get more than 50 percent of the
total votes nationwide otherwise form a coalition government with
other parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
