<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pursues Name-Brand Strategy to Invigorate Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Confidence in Chinese-produced
goods has been increasing among Chinese consumers as they've come
to realize that a group of their own name brands are of the same
quality as foreign products.
</P>
<P>
Name Brand computers such as Legend and Great Wall have become
popular among Chinese consumers, and the market shares of these
computers have increased constantly amid cutthroat competition
over the past few years. These brands are now exported to over 100
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a survey conducted by the State Bureau of Technical
Supervision and the State Statistics Bureau found that Changhong,
Conka, TCL King and other Chinese -made famous color TV sets have
seized more than 65 percent of the domestic market share, while
famous domestically-produced VCD players have also occupied half
of the market.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the ten best-selling refrigerator brands on the
Chinese market are all name-brand products made in China. Little
Swan, Haier and some other washing machines have claimed more than
83 percent of the country's market. In addition, home-made air
conditioners have taken a 72 percent share of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts attributed the achievements to China's new
strategy of fostering name brands to invigorate its national
industry.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Chinese enterprises have firmly implemented
the name-brand strategy, as they have come to realize that in
international competition, name-brand products hold sway with the
market share and distribution of interests, said Jiang Xiaojuan, an
economist with the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pursues Name-Brand Strategy to Invigorate Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has entered a period when large enterprises and
enterprise groups are beginning to dominate industrial production,
which means that development of name-brand products will increase
their ability to compete, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Shunde in southern China's Guangdong Province, more
than 260 major enterprises have set up technology development
centers. Some of the high-tech products, with high quality and low
production costs, have rapidly worked their way into the market.
</P>
<P>
Shunde, formerly a small city on the Pearl River Delta, has now
made a name for itself in the country for Rongsheng refrigerators,
Meidi electronic appliances, Kelong air conditioners, and Gelanshi
microwave ovens.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the name-brand strategy has enabled its
enterprises to make breakthroughs in technological improvement
within a short period of time. At present, the city has 75
enterprises each with an annual sales exceeding 100 million
yuan (about 12 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The city government of Qingdao, Shandong Province, where the
headquarters of Haier, China's largest household electronic
appliances producer, is based, has lent support to the firm in all
aspects, such as financing, taxation, credits, foreign
exchanges and investment. The annual sales of Haier has
topped 6.21 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the course of carrying out the name-brand strategy, Chinese
firms have started to pay closer attention to modern marketing
expertise, said an economist with the Research Institute of
Financing and Trade under the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"This marks a great shift in the production and management
strategies of Chinese firms," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
TV manufacturing giant Changhong, considered the brightest spot
of China's national industry, has come up with an ambitious plan
to edge into the exclusive international club of 500 top
enterprises at the beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
Sales of Changhong TV sets ranked first in China for eight
years in a row, reaching 4.8 million units last year. The
government has extended to it a series of favorable policies to
help it accelerate expansion, said Ni Runfeng, chairman of the
Changhong Electronics Group.
</P>
<P>
To rejuvenate the national industry, the Chinese government has
set a target that by 2010, major industries are expected to churn
out a group of name-brand products which are competitive in the
international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
