<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Records Lowest Inflation in Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand registered an
inflation of 1.1 percent in the year ending June this year, the
lowest since June 1994, Statistics New Zealand said today.
</P>
<P>
The three-year low figure was achieved thanks to falling
transport cost and mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
Calculated accordingly, the Reserve Bank estimated that the
underlying inflation rate - the Bank's measurement for inflation
which excludes interest rate movements and one-off price shocks -
at 0.3 percent for the June quarter and 1.5 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash is contracted with the
government to keep underlying inflation below 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics NZ figures show that in the June year, three of the
nine groups that make up the consumer price index (CPI) recorded
increases while six recorded falls.
</P>
<P>
The major rise came from the housing group, including house and
land prices and rents.
</P>
<P>
However, construction costs, which had risen every year since
1981, fell 1.1 percent in the year under review.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
