<HEADLINE> Pakistan Likely to Unveil Export-oriented Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
likely to announce an export-oriented trade policy today after the
Cabinet approval showering incentive to exporters, official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry is likely to set a 9.5 billion US dollars
export target besides an 11.8 billion import target, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Steps to lower trade barriers to neighboring countries will
also be taken, they said.
</P>
<P>
The government also has plans to allow the import of
semi-finished goods and its re-export after value-addition, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Besides announcing incentives for the export of non-traditional
items, measures will be taken to boost the export of traditional
goods including textiles, carpets and leather, they said.
</P>
<P>
The trade policy for 1997-1998 will be announced by Commerce
Minister Ishaq Dar in his televised address to the nation today,
they said.  
