<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Political Parties Differ over Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Major political parties in
Bangladesh differ in their stands on today's strike called by a
grouping of Islamic organizations to protest a Zionist act of
blasphemy against the Holy Quran.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic groups called a dawn-to-dusk strike on July 3. Five
days later, Jamaat-e-Islami, the country's fourth largest party,
called an eight-hour strike for the same day and the same reason.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that a Jewish woman on June 28 pasted some
anti-Muslim hate posters to about 20 Arab storefronts in the West
Bank city of Hebron. The posters depicting the Muslim Prophet
Mohammad as a pig stomping on the Koran has provoked strong
condemnation from across the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), at its
Standing Committee meeting on July 11, extended its support to the
strike call.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the ruling Awami (People's) League (AL)
Zillur Rahman, however, opposed the strike, saying that it served
political motives of a "vested quarter."
</P>
<P>
He said the AL cannot support the strike as the parliament had
already unanimously adopted a resolution strongly condemning the
offending act against the Holy Quran.
</P>
<P>
The third largest Jatiya (national) Party, which supported the
AL in forming the government, also protested today's strike. But
the dissident group of JP led by Shah Moazzem and Kazi Zafar have
extended their support to the strike program.
</P>
<P>
It will be the third nationwide strike enforced by the
opposition parties this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
