<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov Suggests Regional Conflicts Be Addressed in NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov told his British counterpart Robin Cook here today that
regional conflicts should be addressed in the Russia-NATO
ministerial meeting scheduled for September in New York.
</P>
<P>
When talking about the agenda of the meeting, Primakov
suggested that the issue of Bosnia be discussed and that an armed
force made of both Russian and NATO troops be set up to deal with
possible regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-NATO's partnership council, set up under a landmark
pact signed in May giving Moscow a say in some of the NATO's
affairs, is to hold its first ministerial meeting in September
during the United Nations' General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Cook's visit was aimed at improving strained relations with
Russia at a time of NATO enlargement and an apparent Western
crackdown on fugitive war crimes suspects in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Last week, NATO officially invited the Czech Republic, Hungary
and Poland to join the military alliance. And last Thursday
NATO-led peacekeeping force in Bosnia shot dead a former Bosnian
Serb police chief and arrested a hospital director.
</P>
<P>
Russia bitterly criticized NATO's swoop on suspected Bosnian
war criminals and its recent enlargement, describing the latter as
"the biggest mistake in Europe since the end of World War Two".
</P>
<P>
As for the military alliance's further expansion, Cook told
reporters that NATO would consider the next wave of applications
according to the situation of that time, adding that NATO's door
would remain open all the time.
</P>
<P>
Cook was the first British cabinet minister to visit Russia
since the Labor Party won the May 1 election, ending 18 years of
Conservative rule in Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
