<HEADLINE> Soeharto Calls for Boosting South-South Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto has
stressed the need to strengthen cohesion and unity among
developing countries to boost South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a banquet in honor of visiting South African
President Nelson Mandela at the State Palace here last night,
Soeharto congratulated South Africa on its appointment to host the
Non-Aligned Movement summit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia supports the leadership of South Africa in this
movement," he said.
</P>
<P>
"After the end of the cold war, we have made adjustments to
make the movement relevant to significant changes occurring in the
world as well as to enable it to attain our initial goals," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto also urged developing countries grouped in the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) to refrain from confrontation with
developed nations.
</P>
<P>
"Since the holding of the 10th Non-Aligned summit in Jakarta
(in 1992), we have abandoned confrontations with developed
nations. Instead, we have been promoting partnerships with them,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Mandela praised Indonesia's socio-economic achievements under
the leadership of President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
"You have changed your country from a major importer of food to
one based on self-sufficiency, your experience in this regard will
be valuable to many countries in the developing world, not the
least on our African Continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who arrived here on Monday for a three-day state visit
to Indonesia focusing on economic links, said trade between the
two countries had increased four-fold in the past four year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, bilateral trade stood at about 200 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto and Mandela will hold talks today and witness the
signing of an agreement on double taxation avoidance between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will fly to Bangkok, Thailand on July 16 to begin an
official two-day visit there.  
</P>
