<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> River Harnessment in Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has made great progress in harnessing the Liaohe
River thanks to the just-completed reconstruction of a floodgate
on the well-known waterway.
</P>
<P>
The Shuangtaizi floodgate, which was originally built in the 1960s,
is 60 km away from the mouth of the river. It is a key water
control project on the river to prevent the backward flow of sea
tides and to control the flood waters. It also offers an important
water supply for local economic development.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the sluice gate has been almost completely
blocked by silt, seriously weakening its capacity of flood
discharge and threatening the safety of nearby areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the provincial government allocated more than 47
million yuan for the improvement of the water gate, which was
designed to control serious flooding that occurs once within 50
years and supply 800 million cu m of water to the neighboring
farmland and fertilizer plants per year.
</P>
<P>
The local government harnessed the Liaohe River during the
1986-1990 period, aiming to control serious flooding that occurs
once within 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Central and the local governments have raised money in recent
years to harness the river and improve its capability to fight
floods.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to contribute to the economic development in
the large number of cities and grain production bases along the
Liaohe River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Loses 27% Urban Water Due to Pipe Leakage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 14 (Xinhua) -- About 27 percent of Italy's urban
water is lost due to leaking and oozing during running in
ill-maintained pipes, a survey by an Italian agency showed today.
</P>
<P>
Poor management and bad maintenance of the country's 6,200
major water pipelines are to blame for the shocking waste of
water, which has caused water shortage in the entire south of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The heavy leakage in Emilia-Romagna region has driven the water
price as much as 10,000 liras (6 U.S. dollars) per liter, the
report said. 
</P>
