<HEADLINE> Education Top on Agenda of Summit of Americas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Education will be top on the
agenda of the second summit of the Americas to be held in Santiago
in April, 1998, a Chilean Foreign Ministry official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The principal idea that dominates the agenda is education, as
a basic tool for overcoming the difficulties of development on the
continent," Juan Martabit, a Foreign Ministry official for
American affairs said.
</P>
<P>
The second issue is the promotion of democracy and human
rights, said Martabit, who is the general coordinator of the
summit.
</P>
<P>
He said the third question in discussion will be "economic
integration and free trade", which include the enormous
undertaking of the FTAA (Free Trade Area of the Americas) and
matters such as capital markets, regional energy integration and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He said it would be more convenient if U.S. President Bill
Clinton were to show up at the summit to give credibility to the
creation of the FTAA.
</P>
<P>
The summit will deal with other issues such as corruption, drug
trafficking and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Martabit announced that during the summit, the heads of state
and government will sign two documents: a political statement and
an action plan that is being worded among the participants of the
summit. 
</P>
