<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Join Anti-poverty Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 15,000 ha of Chinese
chestnut trees in Dongyuan County, Guangdong Province, didn't
bear fruit for nearly 10 years until 1993, when researchers at the
provincial Academy of Agricultural Sciences went to the area to
provide technical help.
</P>
<P>
China's poverty-stricken areas have long been plagued by poor
education and lack of well-trained people. Therefore, improving
people's education and skills is considered key to poverty relief.
</P>
<P>
The province sent 4,000 professionals from 48 research
institutes to 50 poor counties in mountainous areas. The experts
have maintained long-term contacts with the counties, and helped
them bring in more than 10 million yuan of investment and 120
million yuan of bank loans.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 1.1 billion yuan in output value was generated and
100,000 technicians and management staff from trained 1992 to the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts have transformed Nanxiong City's cottage industry of
growing gingkoes into a pillar industry by shortening the
fruit-bearing time from 15 years to only five years. The city now
has more than 3,300 ha of gingkoes.
</P>
<P>
The institutions also help the poverty-stricken areas import
technology and provide economic information for the needy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
