<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik Decree, Implementation of Peace Deal Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Tajik President Imomali Rakhmonov
today signed a decree implementing an agreement on achieving
national peace and harmony, and a mutual pardon pact with the
oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, the government would draw up a plan within a
week to implement the accord on peace and harmony, which it struck
with the oppositions in Moscow on June 27, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A special coordination group, to be headed by Deputy Prime
Minister Akil Akilov, would be set up to take charge of the
implementation of the accord, which was aimed at ending the
five-year civil war in the Central Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the peace deal, the two sides would exchange
prisoners of war and establish a 26-member national commission for
reconciliation, to be led by Islamic opposition leader Abdullo
Nuri.
</P>
<P>
The commission, made up by government and opposition
representatives, had already drawn up plans for legislative
elections next year, and the composition of a coalition
government, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of government posts must be given over to the
opposition, and opposition forces must integrate with government
forces or lay down their weapons, according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the mutual pardon pact, which was already signed by Nuri
last week and was to come into effect after the signing of the
president, both sides agreed to free captives seized after
military conflicts broke out in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Since its independence in 1991, conflicts among political,
religious and ethnic groups in the country have left thousands of
people dead and many more homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik government has speeded up reconciliation with the
oppositions since 1995. Large scale fighting ended after a truce
was signed in December last year, but sporadic clashes continued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
