<HEADLINE> China Pull out of Indonesia Badminton Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China has to pull out of the
Indonesia Open badminton tournament because the host nation failed
to issue the team visas on time, Chinese head coach Li Yongbo said
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The competition has already begun today, but the Chinese
players are still at home. Li said they only got their visas
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
``The late visa-issuing prevented the Chinese team from
travelling on time,'' said Li.
</P>
<P>
Li revealed China planned to send all its top shuttlers to
the "prestigous event, including world women's singles title
holder Ye Zhaoying, world and Olympic women's doubles champion Ge
Fei and Gujun.
</P>
<P>
"The host told us last night that we can leave for Jakarta
today, but the competition will be in full swing when we arrive
there."
</P>
<P>
Although the Indonesian Badminton Association promised to
postpone Chinese players' matches by one day, that will force the
shuttlers to play more matches the next day.
</P>
<P>
Li said if Chinese players fly to Jakarta and take one day off,
some of the players such like Ge Fei will have to play four
matches on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"That is too tough. No one can bear it. To play under such
abnormal circumstance will affect players results and rankings,
so we have to withdraw," Li added.
</P>
<P>
Players usually got to the host city one day before the start
of the competition in order to be adapted to local conditions
and regaining forms.
</P>
<P>
Li said China will take part in Singapore Open next week.
</P>
<P>
This was the third time for Indonesia to grant the entrance
visas too late for the Chinese team, who replaced the Indonesian
shuttlers to dominate the badminton world this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
