<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Economic Growth to Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The depreciation of the baht will
result in the fall of Thailand's economic growth rate this year to
4.6 percent from an earlier forecast of 5.6 percent, according to
the National Economic and Social Development Board.
</P>
<P>
The country's growth rate last year was about 6.8 percent, the
lowest in a decade.
</P>
<P>
The board, which is the state planning agency, also readjusted
the inflation rate projection for this year, from a previous 4.5
percent to 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new forecast is based on projections that the value of the
baht will settle at 28.50 to the US dollar, and it could be
revised again if the baht falls further, according to Wirat
Wattanasiritham, secretary-general of the board.
</P>
<P>
On the positive side, the current account deficit is forecast
to decline to 6.1 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) from 6.5
percent forecast earlier, while exports are likely to increase by
8.2 percent, up from an earlier projection of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year exports growth was near zero.
</P>
<P>
Imports are expected to drop by 2.4 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The export and import projections will also be subject to
further study, said Wirat.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government spokesman Varathep Ratanakorn said on
Monday that a 'buy Thai' campaign will be launched to encourage
Thai people to buy more Thai-made products and to take holiday at
home rather than abroad.
</P>
<P>
The government will also further cut unnecessary spending by
government agencies, particularly on foreign trips, and Thai- made
goods would be given priority in all state procurement programs.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand governor Rerngchai Manakanond said on Monday
that the central bank has also revised its projections, which are
close to those of the National Economic and Social Development
Board.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
