<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Baht Down by 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The baht has depreciated by 15
percent against the US dollar since its float on July 2, according
to Thai central bank Deputy Governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi.
</P>
<P>
"We think the baht has weakened enough, or even a bit too much,
given the current state of the economy," he said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank on Monday announced its official reference
rate for Friday's trading at 29.945 baht to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The reference rate is based on a weighted average of trading on
the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat said the spread between bid and ask prices by local
commercial banks was narrowing, indicating that trading volatility
was easing.
</P>
<P>
The last official midrate before the float was 25.79 baht to
the US dollar on June 30. Since its float, the baht has weakened
steadily, trading at as low as 30.50-31.00 baht to the dollar late
last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, central bank Governor Rerngchai Marakanond said the
baht would stabilize further over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
He said volatility in regional markets had affected baht
trading onshore, adding that he did not expect the baht to
depreciate further.
</P>
<P>
although the central bank is optimistic that the baht could
stabilize further over the next several days, some analysts
believe that baht could weaken further in the next several months,
reflecting continued pessimism about the health of the economy,
especially the finance sector, and volatility in regional trading
of the Philippine peso, the Malaysian ringgit and the Indonesian
rupiah.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
