<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Investment Means More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China is feeling the pressure to
provide jobs for an estimated 160 to 180 million additional
laborers during the 1996-2000 period, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase employment, China needs to add vital
investment, not only by absorbing foreign funds but also relying
heavily on internal fund accumulation and investment.
</P>
<P>
Priority should be given to curbing inflation most likely
caused by increased investment, in a bid to keep prices stable to
help create a sound environment for the country's rapid economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The country can also use bank loans to increase investment.
To cut the links between investment and inflation, the country
should increase residents' direct investment while reducing
assistance through bank loans.
</P>
<P>
To increase job opportunities, the government must readjust
some of its macro-economic policies, especially those that are
oriented towards increasing goods and jobs. Emphasis should be
placed on infrastructure and technical renovations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government must take steps to encourage
individuals to use surplus money to help expand production,
rather than for luxury consumption. It should also develop
preferential policies for individuals' investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
