<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eleven Percent of Italians Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 14 (Xinhua) -- About 6.5 million Italians, or 11.3
percent of the country's population, are living under the poverty
line, the national statistics institute (ISTAT) said in a report
today.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 annual report said the two million poor Italian
families live with a monthly per capita cost of 600,000 liras (357
U.S. dollars). Seven out of ten of the impoverished families,
often with many family members and lower education backgrounds,
live in the south.
</P>
<P>
About 94,000 families, or one out of 20 poor families, suffer
extreme poverty with a meager monthly per capita expenditure of
10,000 liras (59.5 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Children and elderly people account for more than 42 percent of
the poor population, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
