<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Lack Aggressiveness in Business, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The lack of aggressiveness on the
part of Canadian business circle is holding the country back from
being more competitive, a new survey suggests today.
</P>
<P>
Less than a third of chief executive officers (CEO) surveyed
believed Canadian firms are "very competitive", and 29 percent of
them cited the lack of aggressiveness as "most common shortfall of
Canadian firms."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Canada has the capability to do even better --
to turn those aspirations into reality. But to do so, we're going
to have to become more aggressive," said a senior official with
the Deloitte Consulting Group, which did the survey.
</P>
<P>
At present, Canada's corporate passivity appears to be
subsiding, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
And every respondent from a non-multinational company said that
their company would expand internationally in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent said that this would involve exporting goods or
service overseas, while 47 percent were planning to set up branch
plants or sales offices.
</P>
<P>
As expected, the United States was the preferred destination
for Canadians, with nearly a quarter (22 percent) of CEOs saying
they would expand into the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mexico was a distant second, at 7 percent, while western
Europe, China, Brazil and Argentina, were each cited by 5 percent
of CEOs as expansion target.
</P>
<P>
The survey, made public today, canvassed the view of 52
Canadian CEOs whose companies employ 350,000 people, generated 65
billion U.S. dollars in sales in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
