<HEADLINE> Philippine Exchange Rate Seen to Stabilize: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' top monetary
official has expressed confidence that the exchange rate between
the country's currency peso and the U.S. dollar would stabilize
within the next few days, the local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson as
saying there were signs that the peso-dollar rate was stabilizing.
</P>
<P>
The peso showed its stability at the opening of trading Monday,
rebounding briefly to 27.45 pesos to one dollar, but settled at
29.09 pesos to one dollar at the closing of the market. The
reference rate or weighted average Monday was 28.77 pesos to one
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The central bank announced last Friday to allow the peso-dollar
rate to move "within a new wider range" after fighting vigorously
speculators for one week.
</P>
<P>
The announcement sent the peso plunging 11.5 percent to 29.45
against the dollar on the trading floor, after which it settled at
28.08 before trading was soon suspended that morning.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the float of the peso, Singson said the government's
principal concern is to protect the "well-earned" economic gains
of the Filipino people from current currency "turbulence" in
regional currency market.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that it was difficult to determine the exchange
rate level where the market is expected to settle "as the market
basically reflects the collective decision of all the participants
and not just the central bank."
</P>
<P>
But he reiterated that the monetary authority will continue to
monitor market developments and ensure orderly market conditions.
</P>
<P>
He also allayed fears of prices hikes, saying all government
agencies, especially the Price Monitoring Council, had been
mobilized to make sure that no one will take advantage of the
current situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
