<HEADLINE> Echoes From The Mercosur (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Mercosur's First International Food Fair
will be held in Buenos Aires between August 26-29.
</P>
<P>
The exposition is directed to the presentation of agrifood
companies.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine organizers want it to serve as a reference for
the region based on four criteria: professional, international,
specialized and pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
It expects 22 countries to take part but 60 percent of
the exhibiters will be from the four Mercosur member countries.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Bonduelle, a French company and one of the biggest
manufactureres of frozen and preserved foods in the world, which
has 850 million dollars worth of billings a year, will install a
factory in Brazil to serve the Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
The estimated investment will be 12 million dollars and it will
produce, for the most part, frozen vegetables with a production
capacity of 15,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil paid 17.7 billion dollars of its
external debt during the first six months of this year, an
increase of 68.5 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The payments included amortizations and interests and
exceeded the 14.2 billion dollars paid out in the whole of 1996,
according to spokespersons from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
In March Brazil's foreign debt reached 177.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru will form part of the Andean Community
negotiations with the Mercosur to create a free trade zone
between both blocs, pointed Peruvian Industry, Tourism and
Integration Minister Gustavo Caillaux on July 11.
</P>
<P>
"With Peru's re-entry to the Andean Community, we can obtain
advantages for trade negotiations with the Mercosur, which does
not mean we cannot negotiate individually with that bloc," said
the Peruvian minister.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Bolivia will double its exports to the Chilean
market due to a revision of the economic complementary
agreement signed by Chile and Bolivia in 1993. Chile and
Bolivia are both associate members of the Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
With the revised agreement, Bolivia will incorporate 154 new
products to its export quota within the list subject to tariff
reductions.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Chile sold more than 200 million dollars worth of
goods to Bolivia while Bolivian sales totalled only 35 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
After the revised terms of the bilateral agreement become
effective on August 11, Bolivia will increase is sales to Chile
to 70 million dollars by August 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
