<HEADLINE> Fujimori's Popularity Drops: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- At the end of his seventh year in
office, President Alberto Fujimori's approval rating has dropped
to nearly a half of what it was at the beginning of his second
term, a survey showed today.
</P>
<P>
If the elections were to be held Tuesday, 31 percent of the
voters would vote for Lima Mayor Alberto Andrade and only 15
percent for the president, said the CPI company, which conducted
the poll.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered Lima and 11 of the most important cities in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The CPI manager, Manuel Saavedra, said this is a very critical
time for the government because the president's popularity is
nose-diving.
</P>
<P>
According to another polling company, Fujimori, who began to
lose popularity in 1996, was maintaining the support of half the
citizenry in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
The plunge occurred during the second quarter of this year due
to a series of incidents that occurred after the successful rescue
on April 22 of the hostages from the hands of the Tupac Amaru
rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
The pollsters attributed the drop in Fujimori's popularity to
political problems, including accusations of human rights
violations, confrontations with the press, the re-election bill
and alleged cases of corruption.
</P>
<P>
For the CPI polling company, the reasons include what it
described as government errors, such as the recent dismissal of
Constitutional Court Magistrates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
