<HEADLINE> Offshore Oil Fields Increase Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Oil fields in the South China Sea
pumped out 6.78 million tons of crude oil during the first half of
this year, a 31 percent rise over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The oil fields, being exploited through Sino-foreign
co-operation, are expected to increase their crude oil output to 12
million tons this year from 11. 84 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The oil fields are under the jurisdiction of the Eastern South
China Sea Company, one of the regional companies of the China
National Offshore Oil Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Nine oil fields have proven commercially worthy of development
in the South China Sea; eight of them are already in operation.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern South China Sea Company has developed co-operative
relations with 38 foreign counterparts from 11 countries and
regions -- including the US, Britain and Italy. It has signed 43
contracts with foreign companies to recover the oil.
</P>
<P>
In North China, the Dagang Oil Field, located southeast of
Tianjin, has produced 100 million tons of crude oil since it began
operations 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
It produced more than 2.18 million tons of crude oil and 193
million cubic meters of natural gas and verified 125 million tons
of oil reserves during the first half of this year, surpassing
targets set for this period.
</P>
<P>
The field began production in 1964 and has drilled 21 oil and
natural gas wells, with annual production capacity of 4.3 million
tons of crude oil and 360 million cubic meters of natural gas. It
also has a processing capacity of 2.5 million tons of crude oil
annually.
</P>
<P>
Dagang Field, covering a prospecting area of 18,600 square
kilometers in 25 districts, counties and cities, has become a
modern, comprehensive oil and natural gas base integrated with
production, processing, machine building, research and design. It
ranked sixth in the country, with 4.34 million tons of crude oil
output last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
