<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Refuse Muslim Leader's Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine Muslim rebel group has
expressed its refusal to the mediation of a former Muslim
separatist leader for resuming the stalled peace talks between the
government and the MILF, local television reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, vice chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), told the SNN television Monday that the MILF will
not need Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region of Muslim
Mindanao (ARMM), in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
MILF leaders, including Jaafar, earlier welcomed Misuari's
mediation and even met him last week. Misuari was ordered by
President Fidel Ramos last week to act as an intermediary between
the MILF and the government to help bring the MILF back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Misuari was chairman of the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF), which signed a peace deal with the government last
September to end its decades of separatist movement in Mindanao,
the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar, who did not give the reason for abruptly turning down
Misuari's intervention, said what the government should do now is
to show their "sincerity" in talks with the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF will reopen peace negotiations with the government
only after the government troops withdraw from its former second
largest camp, Camp Rajah Muda, in Cotabato province in central
Mindanao, he said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF indefinitely postponed its sixth round of low-level
peace talks with the government after the military seized Camp
Rajah Muda late last month.
</P>
<P>
The pull-out of the military from MILF-controlled areas,
especially Camp Rajah Muda, is one of the four conditions set by
the MILF for restarting the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the MNLF, and it has refused
to join the MNLF-Manila peace accord. The MILF began its
exploratory peace talks with Manila last January, but the talks
have so far failed to make any major progress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
