<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legg Mason Tennis Seeds Survive Heat in First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Seeded players at the Legg
Mason Classic survived their first round today in high court
temperatures that soared to 112 degrees (45 degrees Celsius).
</P>
<P>
The outdoor temperature at Fitz Gerald Tennis Center reached
97 degrees, but ATP Tour officials said the heat coming off the
hardcourt surface was measured as much as 15 degree higher.
</P>
<P>
No. 9 Kenneth Carlsen of Denmark defeated Cecil Mamiit 7-6
(7-3),6-3; No. 12 Marzio Martelli of Italy beat Ivan Ljubicic of
Croatia 7-6 (7-3, 7-5; No. 14 Vincent Spadea of the United States
edged Stephane Simian of France 2-6,6-1,6-1; No. 15 Neville Godwin
of South Africa defeated Gaston Etlis of Argentina 4-6,6-4,6-4;
No. 16 Fernon Wibier of the Netherlands rallied to beat Max Mirnyi
of Belarus 7-6 (7-3), 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
Australian Luke Smith, who won the NCAA singles title two
months ago, advanced in his tour debut with a 7-6 (7-4), 7-6
(9-7) victory over Mahesh Bhupathi of India.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Michael Chang is scheduled to play Tuesday
and American Andre Agassi, playing for the first time since May 1,
is scheduled to play Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
