<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Vice-president Slams Wild Card Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Arne Ljungqvist, vice-president of
world athletics ruling body IAAF, hit out on Monday at his own
body for giving Michael Johnson a wild card to compete at the
world championships despite not being selected by the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
Ljungqvist claimed the decision-making process is completely
mad. "This is an important question on which a decision should be
taken after full discussion and analysis, not through a flippant
telephone vote with a few hours warning."
</P>
<P>
The IAAF announced earlier that it would be awarding a wild
card to the defending champions for the first time at next month's
championships in Athens.
</P>
<P>
"It's a bit stupid when you adapt the IAAF rules to fit the
Americans' rules. Its like putting the cart in front of the
horse. The U.S. should fit its rules with those of the IAAF," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who completed historic 200 and 400 meters doubles at
both the last world championships and at last year's Atlanta
Olympics, failed to make the U.S. team after he missed the
national trials because of injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
