<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Talks NATO With Czechs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today ended a one-day visit to the Czech
Republic after talking with top Czech officials on bilateral
relations and NATO's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Albright spoke in Prague after the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization last week invited the Czech Republic, Poland and
Hungary to apply to join the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
She said that "with a first class ticket to NATO comes the
obligation to make a first class contribution."
</P>
<P>
She commiserated over severe floods hitting the north and east
of the Czech Republic in the past week, and pledged more help from
the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
Albright, born in Prague in 1937, said she only recently became
aware of her Jewish origins.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, she visited Prague's Jewish quarter and found the
names of her paternal grandparents on the memorial walls of a
synagogue dedicated to some 80,000 Czechoslovak Jews killed by the
Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
This was her first visit to Prague since taking on her post as
secretary of state in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
