<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Albanians Oppose Comeback of Monarchy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The final result of a referendum in
Albania showed that most people in the country opposed restoring
monarchy.
</P>
<P>
The figures released today by the electoral committee indicated
that 66.74 percent of the respondents preferred the country to
remain a republic while 33.26 percent welcomed restoration of
monarchy.
</P>
<P>
An early election was called in March after the collapse of
pyramid investment schemes which sparked nationwide strong
protests. The president's ruling Democratic Party resigned after
five years of ruling the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
Under the order of President Sali Berisha on June 29, a
referendum was held to decide the political system of the
country. About 1,423,209 out of a total of 1,986,550 voters, or
71.64 percent, took part in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
Leka Zogu, son of late King Ahmed Zogu, and some pro-monarchy
political groups said they would not recognize the result.
</P>
<P>
Leka, 58, is laying claim to the throne left vacant since his
father fled Albania in 1939 before Mussolini's troops invaded. He
is now living in South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
