<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Study on Fuel Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Experts from China and the United
States are working together to develop technology that will
convert China's rich coal resources to automotive fuels and
seeking more efficient energy use with a minimum of environmental
pollution, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
They have completed a life cycle analysis which assesses the
economic, environmental and energy impact of using China's natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
The research project, which focuses on converting coal in
coal-producing Shanxi Province and other coal-rich regions in
China, will provide a valuable tool to help China's central and
provincial governments make scientific decisions based on the
sustainable and environmentally friendly use of coal resources,
according to the State Science and Technology Commission
Vice-Minister Xu Guanhuag.
</P>
<P>
The research project is being jointly conducted by the State
Science and Technology Commission, the US-Based Ford Motor Co.,
Qinghua University and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
China has limited petroleum resources but abundant coal and
natural gas reserves. The country has been a net importer of oil
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Developing coal-based auto-fuels such as methanol, methane,
gasoline, and diesel is strategically important, for automobiles
consume a large amount of oil in China, and the number of vehicles
in the country will continue to increase along with future
economic growth, said Xu.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the world's top producers of coke extracted
from coal. But this process emits large quantities of wasted gases
causing serious air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Extracting methonol from the wasted gases and converting it to
vehicle fuels can reduce air pollution and save energy, according
to the 3E study report released yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Two major methods are used to produce methonol: converting coal
directly to methonol and extracting methonal from coke-burned gas,
experts noted.
</P>
<P>
The 3E study, started early last year, is a computer-based
method aiming to provide an efficiency comparison between the two
methods to find better technology to convert coal to vehicle
fuels. It's a comparison instead of a new method.
</P>
<P>
The study covers coal mining and transportation; the conversion
of coal to fuel; rational fuel distribution; materials and
manufacturing techniques for vehicle production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's PRI Fails to Maintain Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) failed to maintain the absolute majority
it had long enjoyed in the Chamber of Deputies (lower house), the
official count of the July 6 election shows.
</P>
<P>
The PRI won 239 of the 500 seats, 12 short of holding an
absolute majority.
</P>
<P>
Under Mexico's electoral law, 300 of the seats are directly
elected and the other 200 are allocated under a system of
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
The new legislature will be represented by five political
parties, the General Council of the Federal Electoral Institute
(IFE) said today.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing opposition Party of the Democratic Revolution
(PRD) took 125 seats and the conservative National Action Party
(PAN) got 122. Other seats went to two smaller parties, six to the
Labor Party and eight to the Green Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
