<HEADLINE> Echoes From The Mercosur (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Foreign direct investments in Brazil
reached 7.3 billion U.S. dollars during the first semester of
this year, an increase of 52 percent over the same period in
1996, according to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The increase in foreign direct capitals contributed to the
financing of the deficit in the current account and to the
increase in this country's competitiveness in international
markets.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay and Argentina reached an agreement last
week in which Uruguay will export Uruuguayan automobiles under
preferential terms, announced Uruguayan Industry Minister Julio
Herrera on July 9.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Argentina agreed to extend import licenses to
trucks and auto parts. Herrera also revealed that there
is a binational undertaking between Uruguay and China in force,
oriented to the assembly of trucks for supplying the regional
market.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The meeting of Chilean and Argentine foreign and
defence ministers which was scheduled to be held on July 10 and
11 was postponed until the end of this month, according to the
Chilean Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the meeting is to exchange opinions over an
open agenda of topics of bilateral interest.
</P>
<P>
There is only one border dispute between Chile and Argentina
remains to be resolved: the one in the Southern Ice Fields.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The municipal hall of Montevideo and the
ecological coordination of the Metropolitan Area Society of the
state of Buenos Aires, agreed to cooperate in activities designed
to improve the environment, reported the Uruguayan press.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed on July 11, the Argentine
organization will provide Montevideo with technical assistance
as well as scientific and technological know-how over the problem
of solid urban industrial residues. (to be continued)


