<HEADLINE> UN Chief Appoints Special Representative for Kinshasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today appointed Robin Kinloch of the United Kingdom of Great
Britain and Northern Island as his Special Representative for the
Democratic Republic of the Congo effective on July 14, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Kinloch in currently Director of the Office of Human
Resources at the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) in
New York. Between 1991 and 1993, he was the deputy-Director of
UNDP's Africa Bureau and from 1987 to 1991 the Chief of its West
Africa Division. Prior to that, from 1984 to 1987, he was the UN
Resident Coordinator and UNDP Resident Representative on the
Democratic Republic of the Congo(ex-Zaire).
</P>
<P>
In a statement by the spokesman's office, Annan said "Mr.
Kinloch will be responsible for all United Nations activities in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo. He will endeavor to present
a unified, coordinated response to the priority needs of the
Congolese government."
</P>
<P>
"I have full confidence that Mr. Kinloch will enhance the
relations between the United Nations and the Democratic Republic
of the Congo," Annan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
