<DOCNO> XIE19970715.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Shut Down Two Meat Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- the British government shut down
two meat plants today which were suspected of breaking an EU ban
on exports of British beef.
</P>
<P>
The move was responding to investigations by the Ministry of
Agriculture and the European Commission's anti-fraud unit.
</P>
<P>
"Evidence is coming to light that some UK-based companies may
have been exporting UK beef," Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham
said in a statement. "I am serving notices on two companies
requiring them to stop the relevant business immediately."
</P>
<P>
"There is evidence, too, that the companies in question have
been failing to comply with the basic requirements on record
keeping, whose purpose is to ensure that the origins of meat can
be traced, and falling down on hygiene standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the European Commission announced that
hundreds of tons of beef had been exported from Britain to EU
countries and nations outside the bloc since EU banned export of
the British beef in March, 1996 for fear of eating beef infected
with mad cow disease could lead to people contracting a fatal
brain disease, CJD.
</P>
<P>
The beef was fraudulently declared to be of Belgian origin.
Britain reacted to the news by saying it had already launched an
investigation into media allegations of illegal beef exports.
</P>
<P>
"I am absolutely determined that the inquiries into this
complex affair should be pursued to the end. I am determined to
crack down hard on anyone who runs risks with public safety,"
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government, which came to power in May, has been
trying hard to get EU's beef ban lifted. It fears that the
commercial scandal could delay EU's decision to lift the ban.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
